00:01:25.200 --> 00:01:33.440
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:33.440 --> 00:01:36.880
[Unknown]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Badma.

00:01:36.880 --> 00:01:44.960
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. My topic for today is economic crisis plural, and we'll

00:01:44.960 --> 00:01:50.400
[Amit Varma]: discuss both the financial crisis of 2008, as well as the ongoing crisis in India, the

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:55.280
[Amit Varma]: full extent of which is only gradually and terrifyingly unraveling now. But we'll also

00:01:55.280 --> 00:02:00.320
[Amit Varma]: go beyond this and we'll talk about what makes for an economic crisis in general. How do

00:02:00.320 --> 00:02:05.600
[Amit Varma]: we recognize one? What do we do about it? My guest today is my good friend, Mohit Satyanand,

00:02:05.600 --> 00:02:10.240
[Amit Varma]: who has been on the show a couple of times before. Mohit is an investor par excellence,

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:14.960
[Amit Varma]: as well as someone who can get to the heart of the most complex subjects and break them

00:02:14.960 --> 00:02:19.480
[Amit Varma]: down in ways that anyone can understand. I've learned a lot from him over the years and

00:02:19.480 --> 00:02:24.720
[Amit Varma]: in our circles. He's famous among many other things for having seen the 2008 crisis before

00:02:24.720 --> 00:02:29.200
[Amit Varma]: it happened, and putting his money where his mouth was to profit from it in a big way.

00:02:29.200 --> 00:02:34.240
[Amit Varma]: Mohit feels there is another huge crisis upon us now. But before you listen to the rest

00:02:34.240 --> 00:02:40.840
[Amit Varma]: of this episode and then proceed to an underground bunker, let's take a quick commercial break.

