00:03:35.200 --> 00:03:40.520
[Amit Varma]: Mohit, welcome to the scene in the unseen. Thanks very much, Amit. Lovely to be here.

00:03:40.520 --> 00:03:44.520
[Amit Varma]: Mohit, when you were last here, both the two times that you've been here, the show was

00:03:44.520 --> 00:03:48.920
[Amit Varma]: a slightly different format. It was much shorter. I think the first episode we did together

00:03:48.920 --> 00:03:52.240
[Amit Varma]: was the shortest episode ever, which was about eight minutes.

00:03:52.240 --> 00:03:55.640
[Amit Varma]: Appropriate given my height.

00:03:55.640 --> 00:04:00.720
[Amit Varma]: And the last time we did an episode, which I'm really fond of on what poker and stock

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:05.080
[Amit Varma]: markets teach us about decision making and life in general, that was about just over

00:04:05.080 --> 00:04:10.760
[Amit Varma]: half an hour, if I remember. But I've since moved on to a longer, more leisurely kind

00:04:10.760 --> 00:04:15.640
[Amit Varma]: of format where I aim for one and a half, two hours. And I like to sort of begin it

00:04:15.640 --> 00:04:21.240
[Amit Varma]: now by talking about my guest a little bit before we get to the subject at hand. So,

00:04:21.240 --> 00:04:28.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, tell me a little bit more about yourself. What makes Mohit Satyanand Mohit

00:04:28.240 --> 00:04:30.520
[Guest]: Satyanand?

00:04:30.520 --> 00:04:36.560
[Guest]: So I'm 63 years old. So I've been on this planet a while. I'm one of those people who

00:04:36.560 --> 00:04:47.360
[Guest]: has in the Indian idiom, bellowed many poppers. And, you know, poppers in life are quite accidental.

00:04:47.360 --> 00:04:53.080
[Guest]: You never know what you're going to come up with. But one particular popper that I bellowed,

00:04:53.080 --> 00:04:59.040
[Guest]: which was probably the tastiest of all, was something that I worked hard for, which was

00:04:59.040 --> 00:05:06.240
[Guest]: to go and spend some time living quietly in the mountains and doing very little. So we

00:05:06.240 --> 00:05:16.760
[Guest]: spent six years living in a little cottage in the Kumamon. And I think that that both

00:05:16.760 --> 00:05:24.400
[Guest]: summed up one very deep part of my being and also prepared me for another part of life,

00:05:24.400 --> 00:05:31.040
[Guest]: which is the ability to do nothing for very, very long periods of time, which was in very

00:05:31.040 --> 00:05:36.560
[Guest]: deep contrast to the life that I'd led up until then, and which is now become this sort

00:05:36.560 --> 00:05:44.160
[Guest]: of talisman that I draw upon when I feel I'm getting too drawn into dunyadari, which is

00:05:44.160 --> 00:05:49.880
[Guest]: to say, actually, I can switch off and I can turn that key off and become very, very quiet

00:05:49.880 --> 00:05:57.440
[Guest]: and mellow. In terms of outer manifestations, you know, when people ask you, what do you

00:05:57.440 --> 00:06:07.360
[Guest]: do? So I started life as a management trainee with Hindustan Liver. I then set up a snack

00:06:07.360 --> 00:06:14.640
[Guest]: food business as an intrapreneur. So I was neither an employee nor was I an entrepreneur,

00:06:14.640 --> 00:06:20.920
[Guest]: but working from within a company, setting it up. I set up an ad agency, which failed

00:06:20.920 --> 00:06:26.680
[Guest]: miserably, but luckily within two years, so it wasn't a big drain on my life. I spent

00:06:26.680 --> 00:06:35.600
[Guest]: a lot of time in theatre. I worked with musicians very deeply. I then set up a practice to make

00:06:35.600 --> 00:06:43.240
[Guest]: documentary films, and that little practice transformed itself at least twice. We became

00:06:43.240 --> 00:06:50.080
[Guest]: producers of television software. And even though I then sort of exited from active roles

00:06:50.080 --> 00:06:56.800
[Guest]: in the company, the company has done pretty well. It's called Teamwork Arts, and among

00:06:56.800 --> 00:07:03.840
[Guest]: other things, it produces the Jepra Literature Festival. I still serve as chairman, though

00:07:03.840 --> 00:07:07.960
[Guest]: given my level of activity, I'd like to say I'm actually a couch man because I'm lying

00:07:07.960 --> 00:07:16.440
[Guest]: most of the time. I've, as you mentioned, and possibly the reason I'm here is that I've

00:07:16.440 --> 00:07:22.520
[Guest]: been a moderately active investor. And most recently over the last five years, I've gotten

00:07:22.520 --> 00:07:31.320
[Guest]: into a cycle of being an angel investor and mentor, which has in some ways been the most

00:07:31.320 --> 00:07:37.400
[Guest]: rewarding activity of my life. Though, as I said, the most rewarding part of my life

00:07:37.400 --> 00:07:38.400
[Guest]: is the inactivity.

00:07:38.400 --> 00:07:43.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, I've known you for about 12 or 13 years, I'd imagine. One of the things that

00:07:43.560 --> 00:07:48.200
[Amit Varma]: struck me about you when I first met you and still strikes me about you is your clarity

00:07:48.200 --> 00:07:54.560
[Amit Varma]: of thought and your clarity of thought doesn't come from sort of the certitude of someone

00:07:54.560 --> 00:07:59.400
[Amit Varma]: who knows little and thinks he knows it all. But rather it comes from what and I don't

00:07:59.400 --> 00:08:03.120
[Amit Varma]: want to embarrass you by flattering you too much, but from a place of deep wisdom, you

00:08:03.120 --> 00:08:08.360
[Amit Varma]: know, over the years, I and many others in our circles have kind of learned a lot from

00:08:08.360 --> 00:08:13.720
[Amit Varma]: you and can you kind of take me you know, beyond the journey of your career, which you

00:08:13.720 --> 00:08:19.280
[Amit Varma]: just have, but through your intellectual journey, like in the sense, were you a confused young

00:08:19.280 --> 00:08:25.800
[Amit Varma]: man? How did you sort of over the years arrive at this understanding of the world? This understanding

00:08:25.800 --> 00:08:28.920
[Amit Varma]: of markets is understanding of how economies work? Who was it?

00:08:28.920 --> 00:08:37.240
[Guest]: You know, I want to use one word. Intellectual. It's a word which we use a lot. It's a word

00:08:37.240 --> 00:08:43.600
[Guest]: which we use to describe people like you, public intellectuals. And often people think

00:08:43.600 --> 00:08:58.320
[Guest]: that intellectualism and wisdom are sort of congruent. And I think that I'm not an intellectual.

00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:05.160
[Guest]: I've not read as much as many people like you have. And I'm a very bad reader. I tend

00:09:05.160 --> 00:09:15.480
[Guest]: to forget at the conscious level, what I've read. So if I have any of this so called wisdom

00:09:15.480 --> 00:09:25.720
[Guest]: with which you say you're not flattering me, I must accept that appellation with grace.

00:09:25.720 --> 00:09:36.080
[Guest]: And I think it comes from two things, which are very deeply related. One is quietude and

00:09:36.080 --> 00:09:46.400
[Guest]: reflection. And the other is compassion and observation of other people. I think these

00:09:46.400 --> 00:09:55.840
[Guest]: have been the two most powerful forces in my life, apart from the influences of the

00:09:55.840 --> 00:10:03.360
[Guest]: family. Because now that I'm a father of a grown young man, I can see a very sort of

00:10:03.360 --> 00:10:14.840
[Guest]: clear linearity between my father and my son, both very wise, very quiet. And I'm not like

00:10:14.840 --> 00:10:25.520
[Guest]: either of them. But I think there's some genetic streak of being able to be very quiet and

00:10:25.520 --> 00:10:29.080
[Guest]: not affected deeply by what happens every day. And I think that gives you a little bit

00:10:29.080 --> 00:10:30.080
[Guest]: of wisdom.

00:10:30.080 --> 00:10:35.440
[Amit Varma]: And the time that you sort of spent, I mean, if I'm not mistaken, it's in your late 30s

00:10:35.440 --> 00:10:37.000
[Guest]: that you took off to live in the hills.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:44.800
[Guest]: No, actually, I celebrated my 40th birthday with the final decision to leave. And we had

00:10:44.800 --> 00:10:51.480
[Guest]: we actually moved to the mountains in my 41st year and we came back in my 46th or 47th,

00:10:51.480 --> 00:10:53.120
[Amit Varma]: six years.

00:10:53.120 --> 00:10:57.400
[Amit Varma]: And besides the practice of being able to stay in quietude and not being able to do

00:10:57.400 --> 00:11:02.160
[Amit Varma]: anything and just enjoying the solitude and the doing nothing, what are the fundamental

00:11:02.160 --> 00:11:05.000
[Amit Varma]: reason which it changed the way you look at the world?

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:14.480
[Guest]: To my ability to perceive myself, not usually. I've always been fairly independent in the

00:11:14.480 --> 00:11:25.080
[Guest]: way in which I think and conduct myself. But till I was in my late 30s, I was a very, very,

00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:31.440
[Guest]: very social human being. And there was a lot of partying. Some of it went with the fact

00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:39.240
[Guest]: of being in theater and working with musicians and the social life that goes around them.

00:11:39.240 --> 00:11:46.560
[Guest]: And frankly, it's just me, you know, I like company. But I think I was already by then

00:11:46.560 --> 00:11:55.280
[Guest]: beginning to tire of the repetitiveness of social occasions and so on. And so it's sort

00:11:55.280 --> 00:12:02.680
[Guest]: of that period of six years allowed me to make that clean break between that cycle of

00:12:02.680 --> 00:12:07.360
[Guest]: entertaining and being entertained, which seemed like a cycle you couldn't break without

00:12:07.360 --> 00:12:12.880
[Guest]: being rude, to a situation where I was out of that cycle. And now I could come back into

00:12:12.880 --> 00:12:23.760
[Guest]: a world and in a sense isolate those relationships that actually meant something to me and then

00:12:23.760 --> 00:12:31.000
[Guest]: service them more deeply. So I'm not sure if there's a word really to express this,

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:37.320
[Guest]: because I'm not anti-social. I love company. You and I have spent many delicious days together.

00:12:37.320 --> 00:12:51.880
[Guest]: But I don't seek out and I'm horrible at parties. And it, I think, possibly also related to

00:12:51.880 --> 00:13:07.760
[Guest]: this was the fact that I now believe that every relationship requires or merits very,

00:13:07.760 --> 00:13:20.400
[Guest]: very, very deep nourishing. And it's better to have five or 10 really deep relationships,

00:13:20.400 --> 00:13:26.200
[Guest]: which are not marked by the quantity of time you spend together or the number of glasses

00:13:26.200 --> 00:13:33.600
[Guest]: of wine you drink together, but by the consideration that you give to those relationships. So I

00:13:33.600 --> 00:13:42.160
[Guest]: think it really helped me understand that what I was looking for in terms of my social

00:13:42.160 --> 00:13:49.320
[Guest]: life was depth and nurturing rather than hilarity and amusement.

00:13:49.320 --> 00:13:56.320
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting that you speak about depth and how sort of going to Satholi, going

00:13:56.320 --> 00:14:01.280
[Amit Varma]: away from the world and spending time with yourself helped you in that. And I'm kind

00:14:01.280 --> 00:14:06.640
[Amit Varma]: of struck by the fact that in the last 10 years, especially what has happened to all

00:14:06.640 --> 00:14:11.840
[Amit Varma]: of us and which I find myself fighting all the time is that we are constantly drawn out

00:14:11.840 --> 00:14:17.320
[Amit Varma]: of ourselves into the shallow world of social media, for example, enabled in a sense by

00:14:17.320 --> 00:14:22.960
[Amit Varma]: technology and social media, where it's very hard to get any deep work done, which is a

00:14:22.960 --> 00:14:26.360
[Amit Varma]: subject I've written about in the past as well and a conundrum that I face and I try

00:14:26.360 --> 00:14:31.480
[Amit Varma]: to solve and also, and it seems to be a journey into the opposite direction, which you took

00:14:31.480 --> 00:14:35.920
[Amit Varma]: to Satholi where you go away from the people around you and you spend more time with yourself

00:14:35.920 --> 00:14:40.080
[Amit Varma]: and understand yourself and how you relate to them better. Whereas in the real world,

00:14:40.080 --> 00:14:45.960
[Amit Varma]: we are buffeted by a million shallow distractions from Twitter and Facebook and what's not immune

00:14:45.960 --> 00:14:54.000
[Guest]: to those at all. I think I spent more time than I should on social media by a factor

00:14:54.000 --> 00:15:01.440
[Guest]: of at least 10, maybe 100. And it's always a challenge. It's always a challenge, especially

00:15:01.440 --> 00:15:11.120
[Guest]: when your interests are as wide ranging as mine to not get distracted. And I think I

00:15:11.120 --> 00:15:17.440
[Guest]: certainly need to rein myself in from time. And one of the things that helps me hugely

00:15:17.440 --> 00:15:22.600
[Guest]: in that is A, going back to that home in the middle of the forest. And even though it's

00:15:22.600 --> 00:15:31.640
[Guest]: changed significantly, it still is very quiet and peaceful home. And B, the act of getting

00:15:31.640 --> 00:15:42.640
[Guest]: up really early in the morning and dealing with myself alone for sometimes minutes, sometimes

00:15:42.640 --> 00:15:53.160
[Guest]: hours. So this continual reminding of what really matters and where thoughts and sensitivities

00:15:53.160 --> 00:15:55.240
[Guest]: come from is very important for me.

00:15:55.240 --> 00:15:59.080
[Amit Varma]: In fact, speaking of waking up early, there are times where I've sent you a message just

00:15:59.080 --> 00:16:02.680
[Amit Varma]: before I've gone to bed and you've replied immediately because it's five in the morning

00:16:02.680 --> 00:16:09.400
[Amit Varma]: and I'm just going to sleep and you've just woken up. And yeah, that's kind of how the

00:16:09.400 --> 00:16:14.200
[Amit Varma]: world works in strange ways, even when you're in the same time zone. Coming to sort of economics,

00:16:14.200 --> 00:16:17.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, you're 63 if I meet the 23 year old Mohit Satyanan and then we chat about

00:16:17.880 --> 00:16:23.640
[Amit Varma]: economics, would he sort of have the same views as you do now? Or what was that sort

00:16:23.640 --> 00:16:27.800
[Amit Varma]: of journey like? Were there any thinkers who influenced you? Any books which changed the

00:16:27.800 --> 00:16:29.080
[Amit Varma]: world where you look at the world?

00:16:29.080 --> 00:16:34.440
[Guest]: I was very badly educated, I have to say. You know, I did a master's in economics from

00:16:34.440 --> 00:16:42.040
[Guest]: Delhi School of Economics, which was considered to be a reasonably good place to go to. I

00:16:42.040 --> 00:16:46.200
[Guest]: was, I have to say, very frustrated by that whole experience. It was a good intellectual

00:16:46.200 --> 00:16:54.440
[Guest]: training, you know, to read and distill and reproduce and I got reasonably good grades.

00:16:54.440 --> 00:17:07.160
[Guest]: But I was very frustrated by the very deeply leftist ideology of the time, which was reinforced

00:17:07.160 --> 00:17:14.520
[Guest]: by institutions like us. Thankful, though, that we weren't as deeply leftist as, as JNU.

00:17:14.520 --> 00:17:23.640
[Guest]: But I could still in some very, very miasmic way understand the sheer hubris of central

00:17:23.640 --> 00:17:31.560
[Guest]: planners being able to decide how an economy should progress. I could already see the glimmerings

00:17:31.560 --> 00:17:38.600
[Guest]: of the fact that economics needed to be deeply expanded by understanding the workings of

00:17:39.320 --> 00:17:50.200
[Guest]: human psychology. And it's a great joy to me that behavioral psychology, prospect behavior,

00:17:50.200 --> 00:17:55.640
[Guest]: prospect theory, etc. are now such important subjects. I'm not saying I anticipated them

00:17:55.640 --> 00:17:57.400
[Guest]: or understood how they worked, but…

00:17:57.400 --> 00:18:00.520
[Amit Varma]: But you felt the vacuum that they ended up filling.

00:18:00.520 --> 00:18:07.960
[Guest]: I felt a huge vacuum. And I was incredibly happy to leave the world of economics and

00:18:07.960 --> 00:18:14.440
[Guest]: get into the world of business at age 21. So, if you'd met me at age 23, I would not

00:18:14.440 --> 00:18:19.000
[Guest]: have been talking about economics at all. I would have been talking about sales and

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:26.040
[Guest]: business and, and how to put interesting products out into the marketplace. Economics

00:18:26.040 --> 00:18:34.920
[Guest]: sort of disappeared from my way of thinking until… I can actually put a date on it,

00:18:35.640 --> 00:18:39.080
[Guest]: pretty much. 97, 98.

00:18:39.080 --> 00:18:39.880
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

00:18:40.680 --> 00:18:46.920
[Guest]: Which is when I met two people whom you know well, for the first time, both on the same

00:18:46.920 --> 00:18:54.200
[Guest]: occasion, which was Parth Shah and Varun Mitra. At the time when both of them were looking at

00:18:55.960 --> 00:18:59.720
[Guest]: doing some kind of think tank activity in India, neither of them had launched their

00:18:59.720 --> 00:19:04.760
[Guest]: two think tanks, but they were already thinking about it. And there was a summer of very deep

00:19:05.320 --> 00:19:14.680
[Guest]: meetings and a lot of conversation, etc. And they opened up my mind to Hayek, with whom I saw an

00:19:14.680 --> 00:19:21.480
[Guest]: immediate resonance. Of course, he predated my studies in economics, but he wasn't even referenced

00:19:21.480 --> 00:19:28.920
[Guest]: to in Delhi School of Economics. There was not one single Hayek reading in our reading list.

00:19:32.120 --> 00:19:36.440
[Amit Varma]: In fact, the hubris of the central planning that you referred to was summed up beautifully by Hayek

00:19:36.440 --> 00:19:38.840
[Amit Varma]: in the 1980s with the term fatal conceit.

00:19:38.840 --> 00:19:45.720
[Guest]: Exactly. So, in the early days of both of these gentlemen who both helped to shape

00:19:46.440 --> 00:19:52.360
[Guest]: at least an alternative thought around economics and particularly public choice,

00:19:53.880 --> 00:20:00.280
[Guest]: I was forced to re-educate myself and to read a lot more. And having that background in

00:20:00.280 --> 00:20:07.960
[Guest]: theoretical economics probably made it a little easier for me to school myself in it. And

00:20:08.920 --> 00:20:14.840
[Guest]: this began to draw my interest because by then I was not actively involved in a job or in business

00:20:14.840 --> 00:20:21.320
[Guest]: and had a lot of time to observe. Of course, in between 1991, the economy had opened up hugely,

00:20:21.320 --> 00:20:29.480
[Guest]: and one could see the results of that, both from a statistical point of view, as well as more

00:20:29.480 --> 00:20:37.800
[Guest]: importantly from the lived point of view. Gradually, one was able to shed the starvation ideologies

00:20:37.800 --> 00:20:45.240
[Guest]: that informed my teens and twenties and well into my thirties that shaped the way entrepreneurs

00:20:45.240 --> 00:20:51.960
[Guest]: looked at business and hence shaped our economy. So, one was able to see that whole transition.

00:20:51.960 --> 00:20:56.280
[Guest]: So, this is by way of a long answer to a question, how did I think about economics at 23?

00:20:56.280 --> 00:21:01.080
[Guest]: Very little. I really started thinking about economics seriously at 43.

00:21:02.920 --> 00:21:08.440
[Amit Varma]: Right. And before we sort of like I obviously want to talk about the two,

00:21:08.440 --> 00:21:12.760
[Amit Varma]: but specific crisis that I mentioned in the introduction to the show, which is,

00:21:12.760 --> 00:21:17.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, in the early 2000s, you saw the 2008 crisis coming, put your money where your mouth

00:21:17.880 --> 00:21:23.000
[Amit Varma]: was worked out. Well, more importantly, took some of my money out. Yeah. And of course,

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:27.560
[Amit Varma]: the current crisis, but before that, some fundamental brass tacks, and this is a subject

00:21:27.560 --> 00:21:34.360
[Amit Varma]: you have taught also in various places in given talks about, but if I am to sort of go down to the

00:21:34.360 --> 00:21:40.360
[Amit Varma]: very basic questions of how does an economy function? What is responsible for growth? How

00:21:40.360 --> 00:21:46.520
[Amit Varma]: do we recognize a crisis? When it occurs? What are the factors and parameters we should look at?

00:21:46.520 --> 00:21:55.000
[Guest]: Where would we begin to address this question? So, I would begin by saying that economic growth

00:21:55.000 --> 00:22:06.760
[Guest]: stems primarily from technology. It stems from improvements in productivity. And those improvements

00:22:06.760 --> 00:22:13.400
[Guest]: in productivity are primarily delivered by technology. This, of course, then makes you

00:22:13.400 --> 00:22:18.680
[Guest]: wonder, is it worth studying economics at all? Or should we all study technology? I actually think

00:22:18.680 --> 00:22:26.200
[Guest]: it would be better to study technology than economics. But deploying that technology brings

00:22:26.200 --> 00:22:36.120
[Guest]: you right back into economics. And so, highly simplistic model, but the best models are the

00:22:36.120 --> 00:22:47.640
[Guest]: most simplistic, or the most simple. Is that of a desert island economy, one shouldn't take it too

00:22:47.640 --> 00:22:58.840
[Guest]: literally, but I imagine this small happy band of people living on a South Sea island, and

00:22:58.840 --> 00:23:09.320
[Guest]: and they subsist on palm fronds to hide their modesty, fish, which they get out of the lagoon,

00:23:09.320 --> 00:23:15.560
[Guest]: they don't have to wade more than thigh deep, and coconuts, which they break off a tree. And

00:23:18.520 --> 00:23:24.760
[Guest]: they work an eight hour day, perhaps as a union, which dictates it or some custom or some God,

00:23:24.760 --> 00:23:29.240
[Guest]: which says that terror will strike you down if you work more than eight hours a day. But

00:23:30.200 --> 00:23:34.680
[Guest]: allowing for all the differences between individuals on average, in eight hours a day,

00:23:34.680 --> 00:23:42.840
[Guest]: they're able to break enough coconuts to meet their needs for fat, and in the balance, get enough

00:23:44.120 --> 00:23:47.400
[Guest]: fish to meet their needs for protein. So, they're fully keto compliant.

00:23:47.400 --> 00:23:56.840
[Guest]: And this could go on forever. Because of the mild climate, there's no need for any investment in

00:23:56.840 --> 00:24:06.760
[Guest]: real estate and they're all now how does an economy like this break out into a higher productivity

00:24:06.760 --> 00:24:18.600
[Guest]: zone? The way I conceive it is that there's this one dreamer, as always a dreamer, who says, why

00:24:18.600 --> 00:24:27.720
[Guest]: should I have to spend four hours a day breaking coconuts, climbing up the tree and dangling from

00:24:27.720 --> 00:24:34.200
[Guest]: one hand and with the risk of the coconut falling on my wife's head and the risk of me slipping down

00:24:34.200 --> 00:24:41.960
[Guest]: and so on? Surely there's a better way. And so, this guy has this idea of rigging up some

00:24:41.960 --> 00:24:52.280
[Guest]: contraption with dried palm fronds, some kind of dried weeds that he sees in the sea, etc, etc,

00:24:52.280 --> 00:24:57.560
[Guest]: to pull those coconuts down. And he experiments and he finds that it's not happening. It's taking

00:24:57.560 --> 00:25:03.080
[Guest]: too long. It's not going anywhere. So, now imagine that this guy instead starts for a few days,

00:25:03.080 --> 00:25:09.320
[Guest]: works 12 hours a day and now stacks enough coconuts that he has seven or eight days when he doesn't

00:25:09.320 --> 00:25:14.920
[Guest]: have to break these coconuts. And he experiments with this thing and this thing works. And he's

00:25:14.920 --> 00:25:20.760
[Guest]: now able to bring down the six coconuts that he needs instead of in four or five hours in 10

00:25:20.760 --> 00:25:27.400
[Guest]: minutes. Now, from an economics point of view, we have to understand what happened. The first thing

00:25:27.400 --> 00:25:36.280
[Guest]: that happened was that he saved. He saved coconuts for 10 or 12 days till he had a stockpile of

00:25:36.280 --> 00:25:41.960
[Guest]: coconuts lying in the corner. Savings, we all understand. We know that savings is one of the

00:25:41.960 --> 00:25:51.000
[Guest]: important parts of the fundamental economics equation. Secondly, he converted that savings

00:25:51.000 --> 00:26:00.440
[Guest]: into a tool which worked. This tool is what economists call investment. And this also we

00:26:00.440 --> 00:26:07.880
[Guest]: know from a theoretical view of economics, that savings need to be converted into investment.

00:26:10.120 --> 00:26:17.080
[Guest]: Now you leverage that investment back into the economy. That investment becomes a productive

00:26:17.080 --> 00:26:22.280
[Guest]: investment. You can have done investments too. And that is very much part of this whole crisis

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:32.040
[Guest]: cycle. So it's become a productive investment. That productive investment has led to huge

00:26:32.760 --> 00:26:40.280
[Guest]: jumps in his productivity. So this is a really, really simple model. But I find it very effective,

00:26:40.280 --> 00:26:47.640
[Guest]: both to teach young people the fundamentals of what makes an economy work and be for my

00:26:47.640 --> 00:26:54.280
[Guest]: to remind myself whenever I see something complex, what exactly is happening in the economy.

00:26:54.280 --> 00:26:59.240
[Amit Varma]: So at a very basic level, if I can try summing it up, you've set a virtuous cycle in motion.

00:26:59.240 --> 00:27:04.680
[Amit Varma]: What he's done is he's worked a little hard and generated savings, the extra time that he gets

00:27:04.680 --> 00:27:09.720
[Amit Varma]: because of those savings, which are essentially the savings itself, he then ploughs into the

00:27:09.720 --> 00:27:14.680
[Amit Varma]: ploughs into worthwhile investment, which is inventing this technology, and then puts the

00:27:14.680 --> 00:27:19.960
[Amit Varma]: technology back into his primary job of getting coconuts. And therefore his savings multiply

00:27:19.960 --> 00:27:24.760
[Amit Varma]: further, he has the you know, everybody else also gets to save and they ploughed out into

00:27:24.760 --> 00:27:27.800
[Amit Varma]: more investment of funky things. And that's how

00:27:27.800 --> 00:27:36.200
[Guest]: Now I want you to consider an alternative that this guy, the reason that he saved was that

00:27:36.200 --> 00:27:42.440
[Guest]: his wife had seen on some other guy's wife's fingers, sorry for being sexist over here,

00:27:42.440 --> 00:27:50.680
[Guest]: this glistening pearl. And when he made an investigation, he found that his fellow Islander

00:27:50.680 --> 00:28:02.120
[Guest]: had spent 15 days combing at the far edges of the atoll for this pearl. And so he decides to save

00:28:02.120 --> 00:28:09.800
[Guest]: enough coconuts that he can dive for 15 days. So he dives for those 15 days. And at the end of

00:28:09.800 --> 00:28:18.040
[Guest]: that diving, he comes up with this pearl. He saved, he's used the savings to find the pearl.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:25.000
[Guest]: But that's not a productive investment. Because now he has to go back to working six hours a day

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:31.720
[Guest]: to get the number of coconuts that he needs to feed himself and his family.

00:28:31.720 --> 00:28:35.560
[Amit Varma]: His savings are wiped out and he no longer, he's not increased his productivity.

00:28:35.560 --> 00:28:42.920
[Guest]: Right. So you can have dud investments too. Investments which do not result in any

00:28:42.920 --> 00:28:51.160
[Guest]: improvement in productivity. Whether one should call that pearl an investment or not is a very

00:28:51.160 --> 00:28:56.680
[Guest]: moot question. And I've left it moot for reasons that become apparent when you look at the real

00:28:56.680 --> 00:28:57.480
[Guest]: economy.

00:28:57.480 --> 00:29:04.200
[Amit Varma]: Right. And, you know, when you speak of technology, I would also caution listeners from taking it too

00:29:04.200 --> 00:29:09.480
[Amit Varma]: literally. I'd, you know, interpret technology as being much broader. For example, once I remember

00:29:09.480 --> 00:29:15.560
[Amit Varma]: reading about a thought experiment, where what if in the United States, you could send corn to

00:29:15.560 --> 00:29:21.480
[Amit Varma]: Florida, and there was a factory there which turned the corn into cars. That's fantastic, right?

00:29:21.480 --> 00:29:26.600
[Amit Varma]: You'd think that's an incredible technology. And actually, there is a technology that does turn

00:29:26.600 --> 00:29:28.200
[Guest]: corn into cars. It's called trade.

00:29:28.200 --> 00:29:30.440
[Guest]: It's called the modern economy.

00:29:30.440 --> 00:29:34.920
[Amit Varma]: It's called trade. So you know, they send the corn to Japan, Japan sends back cars. That's

00:29:34.920 --> 00:29:40.040
[Amit Varma]: broadly, simplistically how it works. But trade in a sense is also a form of technology because

00:29:40.040 --> 00:29:45.960
[Amit Varma]: you are enabling positive some transactions through which both people are benefiting and

00:29:45.960 --> 00:29:50.920
[Amit Varma]: therefore both are more productive. And that's also a form of technology. So technology doesn't

00:29:50.920 --> 00:29:56.680
[Amit Varma]: necessarily mean a machine made of bamboo fronds with which you're bringing coconuts down, or a

00:29:56.680 --> 00:30:02.120
[Amit Varma]: machine with which you are churning out more widgets or whatever sort you're making. But also

00:30:02.120 --> 00:30:03.800
[Amit Varma]: these inanimate kind of

00:30:03.800 --> 00:30:11.560
[Guest]: Absolutely. In fact, in sessions where I have more time, I then expand this model to money

00:30:11.560 --> 00:30:17.240
[Guest]: invested in outrigger canoes, which then reach to other islands and maybe the other island has

00:30:17.240 --> 00:30:28.200
[Guest]: tapioca and not just palm and it has a different kind of fish and so on and so forth. And just

00:30:28.200 --> 00:30:33.240
[Guest]: showing what the gains from trade can be and then you can get into all of the standard textbook

00:30:33.240 --> 00:30:39.000
[Guest]: stuff like comparative advantage and resource endowment and so on so forth. But for the

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:47.720
[Guest]: purposes of this particular discussion where we are talking about credit crises and financial

00:30:47.720 --> 00:30:51.640
[Guest]: crises and so on, trade and so on are not that important to that narrative.

00:30:51.640 --> 00:30:54.440
[Amit Varma]: Your key point is savings lead to growth.

00:30:54.440 --> 00:30:57.880
[Guest]: No. It's not. It's that savings

00:30:57.880 --> 00:30:58.600
[Guest]: Well invested

00:30:58.600 --> 00:31:02.120
[Guest]: Well invested. That bridge is the very, very key bridge.

00:31:02.120 --> 00:31:04.600
[Amit Varma]: So savings are necessary but not sufficient.

00:31:05.160 --> 00:31:08.120
[Guest]: Clearly not sufficient because I could have used those savings to buy a pearl.

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:10.120
[Amit Varma]: Which doesn't lead to growth.

00:31:10.120 --> 00:31:13.160
[Amit Varma]: I mean, there could technically be an argument that you're giving the pearl to your wife and

00:31:13.160 --> 00:31:16.440
[Amit Varma]: she treats you much better and you are much happier and that happiness leads to more

00:31:16.440 --> 00:31:17.960
[Amit Varma]: productivity. But let's leave that aside.

00:31:17.960 --> 00:31:19.560
[Amit Varma]: True, true, true.

00:31:19.560 --> 00:31:25.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but yeah, I buy your point. So what causes crisis?

00:31:25.240 --> 00:31:32.920
[Guest]: Crisis, first of all, let me say in the historical perspective is relative, right? So even after a

00:31:32.920 --> 00:31:42.200
[Guest]: financial crisis like the one in 2008, we are all still a lot better off than we were for 99.9% of

00:31:42.200 --> 00:31:50.680
[Guest]: humankind. So crisis right now is in the context where we started to take growth and decadal

00:31:50.680 --> 00:31:59.000
[Guest]: improvement in living standards, etc., etc. for granted. And crisis also relative inter-sea

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:06.120
[Guest]: because the kind of crisis that you saw in 2008, let's say in the West, was pretty mild compared

00:32:06.120 --> 00:32:13.000
[Guest]: to, for example, the kind of crisis that you're seeing in Venezuela today, which is not primarily

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:17.560
[Guest]: a financial crisis, primarily a political crisis. So it's all very relative.

00:32:17.560 --> 00:32:26.840
[Guest]: But if we look at some of the major financial crises in history of which 2008 is the only one

00:32:26.840 --> 00:32:36.440
[Guest]: that one has really lived and subsequently studied a little bit, then I would say that it comes

00:32:36.440 --> 00:32:45.240
[Guest]: primarily from malinvestment, which is why I underline the fact that it's not savings that

00:32:45.240 --> 00:32:53.160
[Guest]: it's is enough, it's investment. Meaning that you make investments, which do not result in

00:32:54.120 --> 00:33:02.200
[Guest]: long term returns and going back into that cycle of consumption. And since savings like anything

00:33:02.200 --> 00:33:11.400
[Guest]: else in an economy are scarce, and they are the lifeblood of growth, when they are poorly

00:33:11.400 --> 00:33:19.320
[Guest]: deployed, then they lead to a deep shock to the system. And part of that shock comes from

00:33:19.320 --> 00:33:26.600
[Guest]: expectations. So the expectations are on the part of the lenders, which are the banks, and they're

00:33:26.600 --> 00:33:33.160
[Guest]: on the part of the borrowers, both of them expect a return on those on those borrowings on the

00:33:33.160 --> 00:33:39.160
[Guest]: money that they've taken. And when they don't come, then they're a shock to the system. They're

00:33:39.160 --> 00:33:43.800
[Guest]: a shock in several ways. They're obviously a shock to the person who borrowed the money and can't

00:33:43.800 --> 00:33:52.600
[Guest]: repay it. They're a shock to the person who's lent the money. And now his or her salary, his or her

00:33:52.600 --> 00:34:01.640
[Guest]: profits, the bank are now endangered. But they also get deeply amplified by the fact that, firstly,

00:34:01.640 --> 00:34:09.160
[Guest]: now, because the banks run on a rotation of that available capital, that now the money that they

00:34:09.160 --> 00:34:16.440
[Guest]: should have got back and now been able to lend to other people is not available. So other projects,

00:34:17.080 --> 00:34:23.480
[Guest]: which may or may not have led to malinvestment, cannot now be funded. So now the source of

00:34:23.480 --> 00:34:29.560
[Guest]: alternate growth also starts getting choked off. And they also get amplified by the particular

00:34:29.560 --> 00:34:37.160
[Guest]: nature of banking, which is fractional reserve banking, which means that for every rupee that

00:34:37.160 --> 00:34:45.240
[Guest]: I have in capital in my bank, the banking system actually ends up lending, to take a number, it

00:34:45.240 --> 00:34:54.040
[Guest]: obviously is impacted by various things that happen. But to take a number is, leads to 10

00:34:54.040 --> 00:35:02.360
[Guest]: rupees of saving. And so that means that if my capital now as a result of deep losses, contracts

00:35:03.080 --> 00:35:10.600
[Guest]: by 5%, then again, to take away simplistic number, it means that I have to contract my lending,

00:35:10.600 --> 00:35:17.320
[Guest]: not by 5%, but by 50%. So that's the kind of shock that comes into the system when you have a

00:35:17.320 --> 00:35:24.360
[Guest]: fractional reserve banking system, and when a vast swathe of loans goes bad.

00:35:24.360 --> 00:35:30.440
[Amit Varma]: So just to sort of demystify it for listeners who may not be entirely aware of, you know, what all

00:35:30.440 --> 00:35:35.720
[Amit Varma]: these terms mean. Now, when you talk about savings being invested, what you're obviously, it's not

00:35:35.720 --> 00:35:39.880
[Amit Varma]: that every individual is investing his savings somewhere, he's putting it in the bank or in

00:35:39.880 --> 00:35:45.560
[Amit Varma]: whatever financial instruments he chooses, fixed deposits, etc. And then it's the banks, which

00:35:45.560 --> 00:35:51.560
[Amit Varma]: which put that back further into the economy. And because of fractional reserve banking, if you put

00:35:51.560 --> 00:35:55.560
[Amit Varma]: in 10 rupees in the bank, the bank can essentially lend out say 100 bucks.

00:35:55.560 --> 00:35:56.200
[Amit Varma]: Eventually.

00:35:56.200 --> 00:35:57.160
[Amit Varma]: Eventually.

00:35:57.160 --> 00:36:01.560
[Guest]: Because that bank makes that money available, the person who borrows the money puts that in

00:36:01.560 --> 00:36:08.760
[Guest]: another bank, that bank then has more money to dip into and loans that on. So it's not as though

00:36:08.760 --> 00:36:14.760
[Guest]: the one rupee that you deposit with me, empowers me to lend 10 rupees immediately. It's by the

00:36:14.760 --> 00:36:20.520
[Guest]: fact that the money rotates through the bank and goes from one bank to a second to a third to a

00:36:20.520 --> 00:36:25.400
[Guest]: fourth, or perhaps indeed back to the same bank, that you get this multiplication effect. So the

00:36:25.400 --> 00:36:35.000
[Guest]: eventual effect through this reserve system can be as much as, as 10x. And in fact, at the time

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:42.840
[Guest]: of the worst crises, like the 2008 crisis, due to a whole lot of other factors and so called

00:36:42.840 --> 00:36:51.960
[Guest]: innovations, I mean, there were innovations, but innovations in the banking system, in some

00:36:51.960 --> 00:36:57.240
[Guest]: instruments, in some cases, the leverage was not 10 is to one, but 30 is to one and 50 is to one

00:36:57.240 --> 00:37:04.440
[Guest]: and 60 is to one. So relatively small variations in the value of what you had loaned out, led to

00:37:04.440 --> 00:37:08.680
[Guest]: massive ripple effects and Wall Street virtually coming to its knees.

00:37:08.680 --> 00:37:13.400
[Amit Varma]: And banks, of course, can either make productive investments, which is invest in

00:37:14.200 --> 00:37:17.560
[Amit Varma]: different kinds of technology, for example, entrepreneurs who are actually going to do

00:37:17.560 --> 00:37:22.120
[Amit Varma]: productive things for the economy, and so on and so forth. Or they can make malinvestments. But

00:37:22.120 --> 00:37:27.320
[Amit Varma]: the thing to remember, I presume, again, thinking in a very basic way, is that incentives matter,

00:37:27.320 --> 00:37:34.520
[Amit Varma]: banks would be responding to incentives and investing accordingly. Did this sort of play a

00:37:34.520 --> 00:37:41.000
[Guest]: part in the 2008 crisis coming up? It played a part. I think when you look at the 2008 crisis,

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:48.520
[Guest]: you realize that crises of that magnitude have enough blame to share among many, many players.

00:37:49.480 --> 00:37:57.240
[Guest]: And it's very easy, depending on your political inclination to point the finger at one particular

00:37:57.240 --> 00:38:04.760
[Guest]: player. So depending on which side of the political system is rendering the narrative,

00:38:04.760 --> 00:38:11.640
[Guest]: one or two players get identified. So I don't want to play that same game. And I would like to say

00:38:11.640 --> 00:38:18.600
[Guest]: that banks were very much the ultimate instrument of this whole game. And therefore, they certainly

00:38:18.600 --> 00:38:26.040
[Guest]: had a huge share of the blame. But one of my pet themes is that, you know, when we talk about a

00:38:26.040 --> 00:38:35.880
[Guest]: free market economy, that's again, really relative, because the one of the biggest ingredients of a

00:38:35.880 --> 00:38:44.440
[Guest]: market is money. And money, the price of money, which is the interest rate is not free. It's set

00:38:46.440 --> 00:38:52.920
[Guest]: by a central bank. And the most powerful central bank in the world is the Federal Reserve. And

00:38:52.920 --> 00:39:00.040
[Guest]: therefore, the actions of the Federal Reserve are critical to this whole process. And due to a whole

00:39:00.040 --> 00:39:12.280
[Guest]: host of conditions that preceded the 2003 to 2007 boom, I would say that the price of money was

00:39:12.280 --> 00:39:22.360
[Guest]: too, too, too low. And there is a truism in financial economics, which says good times make

00:39:22.360 --> 00:39:34.600
[Guest]: for bad loans. And an analogy for that is that if brick became really, really expensive, and

00:39:34.600 --> 00:39:41.320
[Guest]: concrete and steel became really, really cheap, nobody would use bricks to build a house, they

00:39:41.320 --> 00:39:47.720
[Guest]: would use steel, and steel would get greatly overused. So now imagine a situation and this is

00:39:47.720 --> 00:39:56.280
[Guest]: very close to the reality of what happened in in the US in that period, the money is now virtually

00:39:57.480 --> 00:40:03.960
[Guest]: free, meaning that you can borrow vast sums of money from the Federal Reserve at very, very low

00:40:03.960 --> 00:40:13.320
[Guest]: rates and historically rock bottom rates. As a user of money for your business, what are you

00:40:13.320 --> 00:40:19.720
[Guest]: going to do, you're going to say let's get as much of it as possible. And what do banks do? Banks

00:40:19.720 --> 00:40:25.080
[Guest]: essentially sell money, right? And the price of that money is the interest that so they buy the

00:40:25.080 --> 00:40:32.280
[Guest]: money, in this case from the Federal Reserve, and they sell the money to their borrowers. And in

00:40:32.280 --> 00:40:41.960
[Guest]: both cases, the cost is the interest rate. So banks were hiring salesmen, loan salesmen. So

00:40:41.960 --> 00:40:47.480
[Guest]: what they sell is loans, hiring loan salesmen by the thousands, because the money was really,

00:40:47.480 --> 00:40:57.160
[Guest]: really so cheap. Now, inevitably, economics 101 tells us then when you have a huge supply of

00:40:57.160 --> 00:41:03.480
[Guest]: something, you're going to sell it on really attractive terms. So what are those terms?

00:41:03.480 --> 00:41:12.600
[Guest]: In in the lending system, what are the terms, the price is obviously one. But the second is

00:41:14.600 --> 00:41:20.760
[Guest]: the covenants, which are what the conditions by which you sell the money under which you make

00:41:20.760 --> 00:41:28.280
[Guest]: those loans, those are going to become less and less and less stringent. Because in the background,

00:41:28.280 --> 00:41:36.280
[Guest]: what is happening is that the narrative is changing. The narrative is one that all of that

00:41:36.280 --> 00:41:45.160
[Guest]: money is sloshing around. It's driving up asset prices, which means the price of houses going up,

00:41:45.160 --> 00:41:52.040
[Guest]: the price of shares is going up. Employment is getting created, cars are being sold, etc. So

00:41:52.040 --> 00:41:57.640
[Guest]: it's driving up the price of assets, everybody is feeling better and better. So there is this

00:41:57.640 --> 00:42:03.560
[Guest]: bullish fervor in the economy, even for those who are not participants in in the financial market.

00:42:03.560 --> 00:42:08.440
[Guest]: So everybody is really feeling good. What do you do when you feel good? You lower your risk

00:42:08.440 --> 00:42:14.920
[Guest]: threshold, you go into more and more risky things. So this is well documented, the covenants go down.

00:42:15.880 --> 00:42:25.080
[Guest]: And most importantly, in the US at that point in time, stock markets are doing well, etc. But the

00:42:25.080 --> 00:42:34.680
[Guest]: most bullish of all the asset classes in the US will housing, housing prices were going up. And

00:42:34.680 --> 00:42:47.000
[Guest]: in fact, the 2007 2008 crash was centered around housing. How did it happen? Firstly, the symptoms,

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:51.240
[Guest]: which are easier to identify now than they were then, but some people did identify them.

00:42:52.040 --> 00:42:59.640
[Guest]: And it's thanks to reading some of them that I was also able to see them. The price of real estate

00:42:59.640 --> 00:43:10.920
[Guest]: went up between 96 and 2006 to by 92%. So it almost doubled in 10 years. In India, this doesn't

00:43:10.920 --> 00:43:17.880
[Guest]: sound excessive, we're used to that kind of number. But in the US, this was more than three times the

00:43:17.880 --> 00:43:26.840
[Guest]: cumulative increase in real estate prices in the previous century. And the reason for that is that

00:43:26.840 --> 00:43:33.320
[Guest]: previous century. Right? So in the previous century, real estate prices gone up by an average

00:43:33.320 --> 00:43:41.560
[Guest]: of 2% per annum. In the US during this period, they went up by roughly 9% per annum. Now what

00:43:41.560 --> 00:43:49.880
[Guest]: started happening? When people who were making loans against real estate, looked at the data

00:43:50.680 --> 00:43:56.360
[Guest]: to analyze risk, what is the likelihood of this money not coming? They looked in the rearview

00:43:56.360 --> 00:44:04.200
[Guest]: mirror, but their rearview mirror was not going back much further than 95 or 96. People don't look

00:44:04.200 --> 00:44:13.400
[Guest]: back further than that. And they were seeing that in this context, this is the extent by which there

00:44:13.400 --> 00:44:22.680
[Guest]: is a variation in house prices. So what is the risk? The risk is low. And as a result, the margin

00:44:22.680 --> 00:44:30.840
[Guest]: that people had to pay on taking a loan against a house kept shrinking. In India was still reasonably

00:44:31.720 --> 00:44:38.360
[Guest]: conservative about these things. You know, you would look at 20, 25, 30%. In the US, there were

00:44:38.360 --> 00:44:47.080
[Guest]: cases where the margin being paid was five and 10%. And because of the volume of money that was

00:44:47.080 --> 00:44:56.760
[Guest]: flooding into the US banking system, nobody had the time to pay attention. In many cases, even the

00:44:56.760 --> 00:45:03.000
[Guest]: margin was on credit. So people were using credit cards to make the down payment on the house.

00:45:04.440 --> 00:45:09.480
[Guest]: And that down payment was seen as a margin against the larger loan. So actually, the house was

00:45:09.480 --> 00:45:19.560
[Guest]: constructed entirely on credit. And there was this phenomenal phenomenon of the time called Ninja.

00:45:20.520 --> 00:45:27.960
[Guest]: So you had Ninja loans, which were every bit as dangerous as the term sounds. It was no income,

00:45:28.440 --> 00:45:36.920
[Guest]: no job, no assets. So these are the three principles against which loans are made of housing.

00:45:36.920 --> 00:45:41.560
[Guest]: You need to have income and or a job, the two usually go hand in hand, but you could be a

00:45:41.560 --> 00:45:47.800
[Guest]: businessman or whatever. So you would look at tax returns, etc. No asset, but the loan was made.

00:45:48.760 --> 00:45:56.520
[Guest]: Why? Because the house itself was seen as its asset. And then this asset went into this

00:45:56.520 --> 00:46:04.360
[Guest]: exponential increase. And it became like an ATM against which further loans could be made.

00:46:04.360 --> 00:46:08.520
[Amit Varma]: So it's like you have absolutely no money and no way of getting money, but you managed to get a

00:46:08.520 --> 00:46:13.640
[Amit Varma]: loan for a house anyway. And then because you now own a house on the basis of that house, which is

00:46:13.640 --> 00:46:18.680
[Amit Varma]: appreciating in value, you take out further mortgages and get more loans and more money and

00:46:18.680 --> 00:46:27.240
[Guest]: you buy more houses. Right? Right. So there were weird cases of and in fact, I remember writing an

00:46:27.240 --> 00:46:35.400
[Guest]: article for perhaps you when you were editing one of the publications I wrote for, which had case

00:46:35.400 --> 00:46:42.600
[Guest]: studies of there was, for example, this woman who was a part time nurse, who had seven children.

00:46:43.480 --> 00:46:52.440
[Guest]: And she managed to raise $5,000 and bought a $200,000 house. And two months later,

00:46:52.440 --> 00:47:00.440
[Guest]: the house was now valued at $220,000. And therefore her equity in this house went from

00:47:00.440 --> 00:47:10.280
[Guest]: 5000 to $25,000. So now she was five times as rich. And as a result of that, was able to get

00:47:10.280 --> 00:47:15.560
[Guest]: a loan because she was now worth $20,000. Right? So she was able to get a $5,000 loan to pay for

00:47:15.560 --> 00:47:22.520
[Guest]: a holiday to the Caribbean. And other stories of people who did the same kind of thing and then

00:47:22.520 --> 00:47:28.440
[Guest]: use the money that they could draw from the bank to make what they thought was an investment.

00:47:29.480 --> 00:47:35.160
[Guest]: And this goes back to the earlier point, which was to build a deck. So the deck costs $30,000.

00:47:35.160 --> 00:47:38.200
[Guest]: And everybody said, this is a great investment, because now the value of the house has gone up

00:47:38.200 --> 00:47:48.200
[Guest]: by another $40,000. But what they were confusing was valuation of an asset with investment.

00:47:49.240 --> 00:47:59.080
[Guest]: Because the way I look at investment is that it must generate sustainable, long term increases

00:47:59.080 --> 00:48:07.800
[Guest]: in productive capacity. To argue that a deck increases the productive capacity of the economy

00:48:07.800 --> 00:48:17.400
[Guest]: is to forget what the prime drivers of an economy are. So we saw that during this period,

00:48:18.440 --> 00:48:28.760
[Guest]: from sort of the mid 90s to 2006, US household debt mushroomed from 80% of GDP to 130% of GDP.

00:48:28.760 --> 00:48:38.920
[Guest]: So ordinary households in the US suddenly owed their own financial system an additional

00:48:39.880 --> 00:48:48.840
[Guest]: six months of GDP, at the same time as household savings were going down. So look at the peculiar

00:48:48.840 --> 00:48:54.520
[Guest]: dynamic. Savings were going down, which should have resulted in investment going down and perhaps

00:48:54.520 --> 00:49:01.880
[Guest]: being more careful about the kind of investment you made. But instead, they led to this huge

00:49:01.880 --> 00:49:08.200
[Guest]: proliferation of unproductive expenditure, I wouldn't call it investment.

00:49:09.400 --> 00:49:13.400
[Amit Varma]: So let me try to sum up everything that you've kind of just said and tell me if it's broadly

00:49:13.400 --> 00:49:18.360
[Amit Varma]: accurate. I mean, I've done an episode on easy money, which is a series of books Vivek Kaur has

00:49:18.360 --> 00:49:24.760
[Amit Varma]: written. And in that episode, we kind of discuss the damage that easy money which is basically these

00:49:24.760 --> 00:49:29.800
[Amit Varma]: low interest rates, you're making money available to the banks for very, very cheap, the damage that

00:49:29.800 --> 00:49:35.080
[Amit Varma]: they can do. And like you correctly said that that is feared banking, those rates are, you know,

00:49:35.800 --> 00:49:42.760
[Amit Varma]: not set by a free market, it comes from the state. And what really led to the crisis was this

00:49:42.760 --> 00:49:47.320
[Amit Varma]: belief by the likes of Alan Greenspan and the others that this can go on forever, you just keep

00:49:47.320 --> 00:49:51.720
[Amit Varma]: making money cheaper and cheaper and cheaper, and it sloshes out into into the economy, and we'll

00:49:51.720 --> 00:49:57.400
[Amit Varma]: just keep growing forever. But what happened was because the bank had access to so much easy money,

00:49:57.400 --> 00:50:03.720
[Amit Varma]: that they started giving more and more loans out with all this money that they had. And they gave

00:50:03.720 --> 00:50:08.600
[Amit Varma]: them out on increasingly cheaper terms, whether those cheaper terms are in terms of the interest

00:50:08.600 --> 00:50:12.920
[Amit Varma]: rate that consumers paid, or whether it's in terms of the covenants or the conditions that

00:50:12.920 --> 00:50:18.360
[Amit Varma]: went into it. And of course, this was also exacerbated by a bunch of factors, which I

00:50:18.360 --> 00:50:23.400
[Amit Varma]: actually want to do a future episode on the 2008 crisis alone, which is something for the future.

00:50:23.400 --> 00:50:27.800
[Amit Varma]: And I even have a guest in mind, I have to write to him. But there were a whole bunch of complicated

00:50:27.800 --> 00:50:33.880
[Amit Varma]: factors like, you know, they would then they were not worried about the risk of these loans,

00:50:33.880 --> 00:50:39.240
[Amit Varma]: because they would parcel it out in using these complex instruments that were given good ratings

00:50:39.240 --> 00:50:43.640
[Amit Varma]: by credit rating agencies, which were paid by the banks themselves.

00:50:43.640 --> 00:50:50.440
[Guest]: Not just that, there was also an oligopoly, a state mandated oligopoly on credit rating agencies,

00:50:50.440 --> 00:50:51.640
[Guest]: only three were allowed to.

00:50:51.640 --> 00:50:56.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and they weren't autonomous, they were essentially paid by these people. So,

00:50:56.040 --> 00:51:01.880
[Amit Varma]: the incentives were to keep the banks happy, which absolutely cannot work. Plus, you had

00:51:01.880 --> 00:51:07.000
[Amit Varma]: the semi government agencies, Fannie and Freddie, basically guaranteeing all of these loans,

00:51:07.000 --> 00:51:12.840
[Amit Varma]: thus creating a sort of moral hazard there. And you had, I mean, if your Google Community

00:51:12.840 --> 00:51:17.080
[Amit Varma]: and reinvestment act, which is something that came about in the late 1970s, if I remember,

00:51:17.080 --> 00:51:22.280
[Amit Varma]: which incentivize the banks to lend to people who would otherwise not be loan worthy.

00:51:22.280 --> 00:51:27.400
[Guest]: In fact, it was a little more insidious than that, which is that, you know, prior to a particular

00:51:27.400 --> 00:51:33.880
[Guest]: date, I forget the date. US banks were highly restricted in terms of their operations.

00:51:33.880 --> 00:51:39.960
[Guest]: Consumer banks could only operate in one state. And when the government decided that they would

00:51:39.960 --> 00:51:49.960
[Guest]: allow banks to apply for national licenses, one of the conditions was that they should increase

00:51:49.960 --> 00:51:57.320
[Guest]: their share of lending to what were redlined areas. Redlined areas being those areas where

00:51:57.320 --> 00:52:07.400
[Guest]: largely black or Hispanic or whatever, where a very small share of housing and mortgage loans

00:52:07.400 --> 00:52:11.080
[Guest]: found their way. So, they're actually being pressured in a way.

00:52:11.080 --> 00:52:16.280
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the incentives were corrupted all along. So, much as you know, the narrative about the

00:52:16.280 --> 00:52:21.160
[Amit Varma]: typical populist narrative about greedy bankers has some merit, you also have to look at the

00:52:21.160 --> 00:52:26.200
[Amit Varma]: systems and the structures within which they function. And there is a lot of confusion

00:52:26.200 --> 00:52:30.280
[Amit Varma]: around. And there is a lot of blame, I would say the lion's share of the blame to be taken

00:52:30.280 --> 00:52:32.280
[Amit Varma]: by the state. But leave that aside, that's a subject for another day.

00:52:32.280 --> 00:52:39.000
[Guest]: In fact, just to finish off that point, in his book, Fault Lines, Raghuram Rajan, who was one

00:52:39.000 --> 00:52:48.520
[Guest]: of the few central bankers to see it coming, in his analysis, he actually says that there was

00:52:48.520 --> 00:52:58.920
[Guest]: a political and hence policy compulsion to make credit cheap because the lack of upward mobility

00:52:58.920 --> 00:53:06.600
[Guest]: of the working class in the US created a compulsion to make them feel good. And making them, making a

00:53:06.600 --> 00:53:15.480
[Guest]: higher percentage of them household owners and seeing household prices go up was a key feel good

00:53:15.480 --> 00:53:27.800
[Guest]: policy of the government. I almost found that too sort of, too scheming to be credible. But I'm sure

00:53:27.800 --> 00:53:30.680
[Guest]: he knew what he was talking about. Otherwise, he wouldn't have written about it.

00:53:30.680 --> 00:53:35.160
[Amit Varma]: Raghuram Rajan, and this is another classic example of good politics in the short term

00:53:35.160 --> 00:53:40.520
[Amit Varma]: leading to bad economics in the long run. But sort of moving away from what the crisis itself

00:53:40.520 --> 00:53:49.560
[Amit Varma]: was and shifting the focus back to you. You saw the crisis coming, why did you see the crisis

00:53:49.560 --> 00:53:56.280
[Amit Varma]: coming? What were the warning bells and take me through your journey of one beginning to recognize

00:53:56.280 --> 00:54:01.560
[Amit Varma]: the crisis, figuring out that yes, I'm not wrong, this is really a crisis and then figuring out what

00:54:01.560 --> 00:54:05.160
[Amit Varma]: should I do about it. And then all the way through to when the crisis ends.

00:54:05.160 --> 00:54:11.880
[Guest]: Right. So you never figure out that you're right till it actually happens. And as you and I have

00:54:11.880 --> 00:54:19.160
[Guest]: discussed often, investing is a probabilistic game. And it's very, you can never assign 100%

00:54:19.160 --> 00:54:28.920
[Guest]: probability to anything. And today, my thinking on that is probably a little bit more nuanced.

00:54:28.920 --> 00:54:35.240
[Guest]: And I understand something about Bayesian logic, which I certainly didn't at that point in time.

00:54:36.200 --> 00:54:43.000
[Guest]: So I think I also need to go back just in terms of my own personal journey to the period 99,

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:49.160
[Guest]: 2000, when I was living in the mountains, and therefore my contact with the world of investing

00:54:49.160 --> 00:54:55.640
[Guest]: was very, very limited. But there were a couple of points in time when I did spend a little bit

00:54:55.640 --> 00:55:02.360
[Guest]: of time in the city. And very interestingly, for a very brief period of time, I think all of six

00:55:02.360 --> 00:55:16.680
[Guest]: days, I anchored daytime television for several hours a day on CNBC, when they were just beginning

00:55:16.680 --> 00:55:23.240
[Guest]: to move into becoming a stock market channel. And this was also the time of the IT boom.

00:55:23.240 --> 00:55:31.240
[Guest]: And I was like this country hick who'd been pulled out of a small village in Kumau,

00:55:31.960 --> 00:55:38.040
[Guest]: and talking to people who saw the world in a very, very different way. And I was looking

00:55:38.040 --> 00:55:43.240
[Guest]: at investments, you know, you invest in a company, and maybe 20 years later, it's worth something.

00:55:43.240 --> 00:55:49.240
[Guest]: And I found people asking me on a day to day basis, literally, so what is the price of Infosys

00:55:49.240 --> 00:55:55.640
[Guest]: stock going to be next week? And I would say I'll be lucky if I get the price for next decade,

00:55:55.640 --> 00:56:00.920
[Guest]: right, and not next week. And I realized that this was a very, very different game from the way in

00:56:00.920 --> 00:56:10.840
[Guest]: which I thought. And I was very late to the IT party, I bought some Infosys stock at 3500 rupees.

00:56:10.840 --> 00:56:16.920
[Guest]: And I next saw a newspaper a month later, because we didn't get newspapers where I was.

00:56:17.800 --> 00:56:24.200
[Guest]: And I rubbed my eyes because the price was now 4500 rupees and I actually went to an STD booth.

00:56:25.080 --> 00:56:29.400
[Guest]: This is before the days of cell phones, I went to an STD booth, called up my stockbroker and said,

00:56:29.960 --> 00:56:36.120
[Guest]: you know, I thought I bought the Infosys stock at 3500. Paper is now saying 4500. Did I make a

00:56:36.120 --> 00:56:45.640
[Guest]: mistake? He said, no sir, it's gone from 3500 to 4500 and it'll go to 10,000. But this kind of

00:56:45.640 --> 00:56:52.440
[Guest]: dialogue disturbed me very, very deeply. And anyway, I went off on a long trek and I came back

00:56:52.440 --> 00:56:57.400
[Guest]: and reached home in the middle of the night and so didn't pick up a newspaper on the way and maybe a

00:56:57.400 --> 00:57:05.880
[Guest]: couple of months later came back to Delhi. And it was 6500 rupees. So I was very lucky. And I

00:57:05.880 --> 00:57:11.640
[Guest]: saw all in like three months. And this was now beginning to just look completely weird.

00:57:12.600 --> 00:57:20.280
[Guest]: So I picked up a piece of paper and a pencil, I got a hold of two or three of the balance sheets

00:57:20.280 --> 00:57:24.680
[Guest]: in those days, you had to actually get physical copies and so on so forth, and did some back of

00:57:24.680 --> 00:57:31.480
[Guest]: the envelope calculations before I knew how to use a spreadsheet, how to use a calculator, paper,

00:57:31.480 --> 00:57:39.800
[Guest]: pencil. And I said, by my logic, and by the way, I look at the price of money, the share price has

00:57:39.800 --> 00:57:45.240
[Guest]: got to go up the earnings of this firm have got to go up by I forget the number 60% per annum for

00:57:45.240 --> 00:57:50.040
[Guest]: the next 10 years to justify this price. And I don't know of any company in the history of the

00:57:50.040 --> 00:57:55.720
[Guest]: world that has seen its earnings go up by 60% per annum for 10 years. Therefore, this is a sell.

00:57:55.720 --> 00:58:06.120
[Guest]: And I rang up my broker, and I said, please sell the share. And he said, so I said, on momentum

00:58:06.120 --> 00:58:11.320
[Guest]: alone, your guess is good as mine, my guess is it'll go to 11,000. I was just joking with him,

00:58:11.320 --> 00:58:21.720
[Guest]: obviously. But I'm selling today. And we were both wrong because it went to 12,000. But within a

00:58:21.720 --> 00:58:30.680
[Guest]: year, it was 1000 rupees. So in a very, very, very tiny way, I saw what that kind of reckless

00:58:31.480 --> 00:58:38.520
[Guest]: optimism could do to a stock. I'm talking about my personal participation,

00:58:39.960 --> 00:58:47.480
[Guest]: newspapers, etc, one saw, but this personal act of taking a call and exiting in a contrarian way

00:58:47.480 --> 00:58:53.000
[Amit Varma]: happened in that really tiny way in. And this would have underlined the importance of following

00:58:53.000 --> 00:58:57.480
[Guest]: through on your conviction. Correct. And on hard numbers and some amount of analysis.

00:58:58.360 --> 00:59:08.280
[Guest]: So now, in 2007, I saw all the signs of euphoria. The signs were that so I started investing in

00:59:08.280 --> 00:59:18.040
[Guest]: stocks seriously in 2003. For the reason that AI returned to the city after six years be that I saw

00:59:18.040 --> 00:59:22.440
[Guest]: that interest rates in India were the lowest that they'd been in memory. And I thought this was a

00:59:22.440 --> 00:59:28.680
[Guest]: good reason for a bull run. And in 2003, there were several beaten down sectors like consumer

00:59:28.680 --> 00:59:33.560
[Guest]: goods, etc, which nobody was buying. I could see the logic very clearly, I bought them.

00:59:33.560 --> 00:59:37.400
[Guest]: Nobody was buying even my stockbroker, why are you buying this share? Nobody's interested,

00:59:37.400 --> 00:59:44.440
[Guest]: there's no liquidity. So in a sense, 2003, I went through the same cycle of being

00:59:45.480 --> 00:59:51.320
[Guest]: for want of a better word contrarian, you know, buying stocks was on the wrong side of the market.

00:59:52.120 --> 00:59:55.560
[Guest]: But actually, that's the place to be right, you only make money when you're on the wrong side of

00:59:55.560 --> 01:00:05.080
[Guest]: the market. And then in 2006, 2007, I saw all the people who didn't believe in buying stocks in 2003,

01:00:05.080 --> 01:00:12.360
[Guest]: now piling into the market. This was the first sort of sign to me that the psychology is changing.

01:00:12.920 --> 01:00:16.600
[Guest]: And it's when markets start getting really crowded with buyers that you need to be

01:00:17.160 --> 01:00:23.560
[Guest]: looking at in caution. But that was only one part of it. The second part of it and what really

01:00:23.560 --> 01:00:28.840
[Guest]: informed my thinking was some of the numbers that I've talked to you about, you know, here was a

01:00:28.840 --> 01:00:33.640
[Guest]: time as I told you, I had got re exposed to economics, I was getting interested, I was doing

01:00:33.640 --> 01:00:38.920
[Guest]: a lot of reading, the internet was coming alive. And therefore you could read a lot more than you

01:00:38.920 --> 01:00:45.080
[Guest]: could when I was a student in the formal sense of economics. I was a much better informed student,

01:00:45.080 --> 01:00:49.640
[Guest]: I had access to a much bigger library than the Delhi University Library, I had the library of

01:00:49.640 --> 01:00:55.320
[Guest]: the world's publications. And so I could see some of these signs, I could see how

01:00:57.800 --> 01:01:05.080
[Guest]: credit in the US was expanding, how households were taking on debt, I could see this whole

01:01:05.080 --> 01:01:10.600
[Guest]: McMansion phenomenon happening, you know, everybody buying homes, people buying third

01:01:10.600 --> 01:01:19.480
[Guest]: and fourth and fifth homes, people with no income, no jobs, no assets. And by then, I think I was

01:01:19.480 --> 01:01:27.160
[Guest]: fully internalized to this fact that boom leads to bust, and that good times make bad loans,

01:01:27.160 --> 01:01:33.560
[Guest]: and that when loans go bad, the whole banking system goes kaput. So the more I read, and you

01:01:33.560 --> 01:01:39.880
[Guest]: know what, these often very self reinforcing, you start reading something, it leads to a link to

01:01:39.880 --> 01:01:47.560
[Guest]: something else. And this, this conviction started building in my head. And India at the time was

01:01:47.560 --> 01:01:54.280
[Guest]: also going through an unprecedented boom phase. And that boom was being fueled by, yes, we had a

01:01:54.280 --> 01:02:00.280
[Guest]: high savings rate. We've never seen that savings rate again. And I'll come to that a little bit

01:02:00.280 --> 01:02:07.880
[Guest]: later if we get there. We also are experts for booming. Experts were growing 15% per annum again,

01:02:07.880 --> 01:02:13.160
[Guest]: which was quite unprecedented. And because of all of this money sloshing around all over the world,

01:02:13.160 --> 01:02:19.240
[Guest]: there was all of this money coming into India as well. And so the question I had to ask myself was,

01:02:19.240 --> 01:02:24.840
[Guest]: if there's a sudden stop in this whole credit cycle, what is the impact on India going to be?

01:02:25.560 --> 01:02:29.320
[Guest]: You know, is India going to be one of the last places from where the money retreats or one of

01:02:29.320 --> 01:02:36.920
[Guest]: the first places? And from whatever I read in the management literature and the banking

01:02:36.920 --> 01:02:45.320
[Guest]: literature, I came to the firm hypothesis that when there's a crisis, people withdraw to the center.

01:02:46.280 --> 01:02:51.080
[Guest]: So if you have a money manager in the US, the last place that he's going to pull money out of is the

01:02:51.080 --> 01:02:58.200
[Guest]: US. The first place is going to pull money out of is the Cameroons or Bangladesh or, or India. And

01:02:58.200 --> 01:03:11.160
[Guest]: so I came to believe that while in scale, the impact on the US would be the largest in terms of

01:03:11.160 --> 01:03:16.920
[Guest]: time and severity, India as a capital short nation would be one of the first to feel the impact.

01:03:19.240 --> 01:03:23.640
[Guest]: Not comparing it to other nations, since one was not exposed to markets in any other nations, but

01:03:23.640 --> 01:03:33.320
[Guest]: just as an Indian, here was stock markets, which were richly valued in a time when growth and flow

01:03:33.320 --> 01:03:40.600
[Guest]: of capital was its its greatest. And if the engine of that money, which was the US, if the credit

01:03:40.600 --> 01:03:49.160
[Guest]: system got disrupted over there, then we would be the earliest to feel the impact. Now at the time,

01:03:49.160 --> 01:03:56.200
[Guest]: I was writing a fortnightly column in a magazine, which was reasonably widely followed by investors,

01:03:56.200 --> 01:04:02.920
[Guest]: which was called Outlook Money. And I was for the first time in my, for the only time in my life,

01:04:03.880 --> 01:04:12.040
[Guest]: I guess, a journalist with a badge. So you know, I was on the I was not just a byline, I was on the

01:04:12.040 --> 01:04:19.880
[Guest]: masthead, I was consulting editor, and I was writing fortnightly, sometimes two columns in every issue

01:04:19.880 --> 01:04:26.360
[Guest]: on investing specifically on equity investing. And I've been very much a votary of the bull run,

01:04:27.240 --> 01:04:35.320
[Guest]: and very much a votary of shifting money from secondary investments, meaning

01:04:36.360 --> 01:04:40.520
[Guest]: post office savings banks and FDs and so on into primary investments, which was equity.

01:04:40.520 --> 01:04:49.480
[Guest]: But by May 2007, I was so completely convinced that this was about to come to an end. If I have

01:04:49.480 --> 01:04:54.280
[Guest]: the date, right, I may be off by a couple of days, but not more than that. If I remember right,

01:04:54.280 --> 01:05:06.440
[Guest]: on May 23, 2007, I wrote my column and it said, the end of the GIBDR. So that title was necessitated

01:05:06.440 --> 01:05:11.640
[Guest]: by the fact that there was only that much space on the page, which I then said the great Indian

01:05:11.640 --> 01:05:17.000
[Guest]: bull run. So this is the end of the GIBR, the great Indian bull run. Of course, I was completely

01:05:17.000 --> 01:05:25.560
[Guest]: wrong. This was May 2007. And if I remember right, the Nifty was at about 4500 at that point in time.

01:05:26.360 --> 01:05:32.280
[Guest]: And I started exiting stocks. I also started for the first time in my life, I started

01:05:32.280 --> 01:05:41.800
[Guest]: shorting the market through various instruments. And I set a certain sum of money aside, I was not

01:05:42.520 --> 01:05:47.320
[Guest]: naive enough to believe that the shorts would make money from day one. But

01:05:49.160 --> 01:05:56.120
[Guest]: they took much longer than I thought to make money. And for the next seven months,

01:05:56.120 --> 01:06:04.680
[Guest]: my conviction was being questioned every day, implicitly or explicitly by a market which went

01:06:04.680 --> 01:06:11.640
[Guest]: from 4500 to 6300. And all this while you were shorting stocks and losing money and losing money.

01:06:11.640 --> 01:06:16.440
[Guest]: I was writing a check every month to my broker for the stocks I was short. Did this make you

01:06:16.440 --> 01:06:21.160
[Amit Varma]: question yourself and think that am I wrong? Am I missing something? Am I falling prey to

01:06:21.160 --> 01:06:26.600
[Amit Varma]: confirmation bias? You know, so I hadn't met you then I didn't know the word confirmation bias.

01:06:28.440 --> 01:06:40.840
[Guest]: But I questioned my hypothesis. I read more and more and more and more. I went deeper into economic

01:06:40.840 --> 01:06:52.680
[Guest]: history. And I could find absolutely no way to destroy my own hypothesis, except for that one

01:06:52.680 --> 01:06:59.080
[Guest]: ingredient which seemed to be fueling everybody else, which was hope. I actually found nothing

01:06:59.080 --> 01:07:08.120
[Guest]: to destroy that hypothesis. And I remember one day telling my sister, I don't talk much about

01:07:08.120 --> 01:07:12.920
[Guest]: finance and economics with anybody in my family, because they never questioned me, they're not

01:07:12.920 --> 01:07:21.880
[Guest]: interested. They're all people of very modest needs. And those get met quite simply. But I

01:07:21.880 --> 01:07:27.800
[Guest]: remember one day, telling my sister, she I think she may have asked me, how come there's so much

01:07:27.800 --> 01:07:32.760
[Guest]: money lying in my account? Meaning, like, why have you sold the stock? And why is there all this

01:07:32.760 --> 01:07:39.960
[Guest]: cash lying there? So I remember the words with which I said, you know, it's like I'm standing

01:07:39.960 --> 01:07:47.560
[Guest]: at the railway crossing and I can see this train coming. And I know that it's about to crash. But

01:07:47.560 --> 01:07:53.240
[Guest]: when I point it out to other people, they can't see it. And the train keeps on coming and the train

01:07:53.240 --> 01:08:04.440
[Guest]: keeps on coming. And I rubbed my eyes and I read more and nothing changed my view. And, and of

01:08:04.440 --> 01:08:08.680
[Guest]: course, you were, you know, aware of the saying that the markets can stay irrational more than

01:08:08.680 --> 01:08:15.640
[Amit Varma]: an individual can stay solvent. Oh, yes, I was acutely aware of it. And more so because as I was

01:08:15.640 --> 01:08:20.840
[Guest]: sort of hatching this idea, I was thinking, well, I'm going to go and buy a train. And I

01:08:20.840 --> 01:08:26.440
[Guest]: was more so because as I was sort of hatching this plot and drawing data and talking to people and

01:08:26.440 --> 01:08:33.880
[Guest]: so on so forth, I acquired a co conspirator, a person who was probably more financially literate

01:08:33.880 --> 01:08:42.120
[Guest]: than me was a full time markets person. And we both started taking shorts together. And

01:08:43.560 --> 01:08:48.680
[Guest]: after three and a half or four months, he rung me up and almost apologetically, it's not that our

01:08:48.680 --> 01:08:53.640
[Guest]: money was pooled or anything, we were just working in parallel. But almost apologetically, he told me,

01:08:53.640 --> 01:08:58.440
[Guest]: I'm getting out, because I'm having sleepless nights, and it's not worth it.

01:09:00.600 --> 01:09:07.160
[Guest]: Luckily, I never had sleepless nights. So I think part of it was that I sort of

01:09:09.160 --> 01:09:18.280
[Guest]: set a sum aside and circumscribe that sum. And actually, I would have sought to exhausted that

01:09:18.280 --> 01:09:29.240
[Guest]: sum by March of 2008. But between January 20, and Republic Day, I think it was 21st and 22nd,

01:09:29.240 --> 01:09:40.600
[Guest]: or 22nd and 23rd. The nifty tank like 15% in two days. So I made up all the money that I'd

01:09:42.440 --> 01:09:46.920
[Guest]: frittered away, or if you want to say in retrospect, invested in shorts,

01:09:46.920 --> 01:09:52.360
[Guest]: it all came back in two days. And then of course, went on through 2008.

01:09:52.360 --> 01:09:53.880
[Guest]: Guy Ready And you kept making money through

01:09:53.880 --> 01:09:53.880
[Guest]: it.

01:09:53.880 --> 01:09:55.960
[Guest]: Professor Karan Devi I kept making money, I kept making money.

01:09:56.920 --> 01:10:01.880
[Guest]: I continued the shorts. And, but I,

01:10:05.000 --> 01:10:10.360
[Guest]: so I actually did three things. One is that I took money out of the market, you know,

01:10:10.360 --> 01:10:14.680
[Guest]: I liquidated part of the portfolio. And they just sat on the sidelines, you know,

01:10:14.680 --> 01:10:21.320
[Guest]: the money in my sister's account, for example. The second thing that I did was with a very tiny

01:10:21.320 --> 01:10:33.160
[Guest]: sum of money. So it was a small, it was a small pile. I took on shorts. And those of course,

01:10:33.160 --> 01:10:41.400
[Guest]: did extraordinarily well as a return on that, on that starting pool. You know, in those kinds of

01:10:41.400 --> 01:10:46.360
[Guest]: situations, returns are not measured in percent per annum, they're measured in

01:10:46.360 --> 01:10:53.160
[Guest]: multiples per annum. But again, I want to underline that the pool was very, very small.

01:10:53.800 --> 01:11:01.560
[Guest]: But a third thing that I did, which was in a sense, one of my few own personal experience of

01:11:02.360 --> 01:11:07.960
[Guest]: what Howard Marks calls second order thinking, was to try and figure, okay,

01:11:07.960 --> 01:11:14.440
[Guest]: that let's assume that this debt crisis happens, and how are governments going to react?

01:11:15.720 --> 01:11:25.240
[Guest]: And the only way I saw them doing it was to further lower the price of money,

01:11:26.440 --> 01:11:31.080
[Guest]: because then the cost of servicing those loans goes down. So if you want the banks to become

01:11:31.080 --> 01:11:37.880
[Guest]: healthy again, you want to make it easier for them to repay the money. And you possibly want to give

01:11:37.880 --> 01:11:42.440
[Guest]: them more money, you want to give them more money on terms which don't make it difficult for them.

01:11:42.440 --> 01:11:51.160
[Guest]: So you start dropping the price of money now, because in most of the world, money is very,

01:11:51.160 --> 01:11:59.160
[Guest]: very fluid, it flows from one jurisdiction to another. I imagined a scenario where central

01:11:59.160 --> 01:12:04.280
[Guest]: banks around the world were going to start competing to reduce the cost of money,

01:12:05.560 --> 01:12:11.800
[Guest]: both to depreciate, both to make it easier for banks and other financial institutions to repay,

01:12:12.760 --> 01:12:17.640
[Guest]: as well as to drive up exports, which then everybody would feel the need for.

01:12:18.440 --> 01:12:25.640
[Guest]: And in that kind of competitive depreciation, what I saw happening is people taking recourse to

01:12:25.640 --> 01:12:35.800
[Guest]: gold as a hedge for a non-depreciating currency. So, you know, unlike a dollar,

01:12:35.800 --> 01:12:43.640
[Guest]: which occurs on balance sheets, both on the asset and the liability side, gold is an asset which

01:12:43.640 --> 01:12:47.400
[Guest]: you can hold without there being a counterparty on the other side. And therefore, it becomes

01:12:48.200 --> 01:12:54.440
[Guest]: a very attractive place to go to when currency stability is a question. You know, you don't

01:12:54.440 --> 01:13:02.600
[Guest]: know how the dollar is going to move against the euro. And so if you're in euro, you don't want

01:13:02.600 --> 01:13:06.600
[Guest]: to be in dollar any longer, you don't know how the yen is going to behave, you're certainly not

01:13:06.600 --> 01:13:11.480
[Guest]: interested in the rupee, and so you're going to. So this was sort of second order thinking.

01:13:11.480 --> 01:13:13.480
[Guest]: And you put a lot of money into gold.

01:13:13.480 --> 01:13:20.360
[Guest]: I put a fair amount of money into gold. And that, of course, did phenomenally well. It just went on

01:13:20.360 --> 01:13:30.440
[Guest]: this crazy bull run from about $700 an ounce in 2007. I think it peaked at about $1,800 by 2012.

01:13:30.440 --> 01:13:36.840
[Guest]: And meanwhile, the rupee also went down. So the return you got was a product of two things.

01:13:37.720 --> 01:13:40.040
[Guest]: See, I did all of these three in retrospect.

01:13:43.640 --> 01:13:47.000
[Guest]: But it's easy to say that I would have taken a much larger pool of money to

01:13:47.000 --> 01:13:52.120
[Guest]: short on, you know, I've got a lot more gold, but you know, that's very easy to say.

01:13:53.160 --> 01:13:57.480
[Amit Varma]: But that's a hindsight bias. But the very fact that you saw it coming and you actually acted

01:13:57.480 --> 01:14:03.640
[Amit Varma]: on it and took the great risk of losing a lot of money, whether in terms of, you know, nominal

01:14:03.640 --> 01:14:08.760
[Amit Varma]: returns, or you know, just actually losing the money is quite something you had skin in the game

01:14:08.760 --> 01:14:09.480
[Amit Varma]: as Talib would say.

01:14:09.480 --> 01:14:16.280
[Guest]: Talib invites very, very mixed reactions. But I think some people are very, very

