01:18:07.320 --> 01:18:11.720
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back, you're listening to The Scene in the Unseen with me, Amit Verma. And my guest today is

01:18:11.720 --> 01:18:17.640
[Amit Varma]: Mohit Satyanand, who's just finished telling us about how he made tons of money off the 2008

01:18:17.640 --> 01:18:23.240
[Guest]: financial crisis. I wouldn't call it tons, Amit, but yeah, it was the beginning of a small nest egg.

01:18:23.880 --> 01:18:29.720
[Amit Varma]: The beginnings of a small nest egg. I mean, nest egg. Yeah, I mean, like you said, the crisis are

01:18:29.720 --> 01:18:35.240
[Amit Varma]: relative and so is tons. So for me, I'm sure it would be tons. But let's get kind of to the meat

01:18:35.240 --> 01:18:40.120
[Amit Varma]: of the episode. I mean, what what prompted me to ask you to come on the show was a chat we were

01:18:40.120 --> 01:18:47.560
[Amit Varma]: having a couple of evenings ago, where you were giving me all your reasons for why we are not just

01:18:47.560 --> 01:18:51.720
[Amit Varma]: in a crisis now, but it's a worse crisis and people think or acknowledge and it's only going to get

01:18:51.720 --> 01:18:57.160
[Amit Varma]: worse. And this is obviously a very different kind of crisis. Nothing else. It's very, very different.

01:18:57.800 --> 01:19:07.960
[Guest]: It's very, very different. And there's several components to it. So let me sort of try and

01:19:07.960 --> 01:19:16.680
[Guest]: unravel and outline some of them, which can't be done as elegantly as you do with something which

01:19:16.680 --> 01:19:23.560
[Guest]: you look at in hindsight, and which has been widely and deeply reported upon and has been

01:19:23.560 --> 01:19:30.440
[Guest]: the subject of several very, very erudite books and hundreds of doctoral theses and so on and so

01:19:30.440 --> 01:19:45.960
[Guest]: forth. But I think that we have to look at the current Indian situation very much as a continuum

01:19:45.960 --> 01:19:56.440
[Guest]: of what happened in 2008. Where like the rest of the world, we suffered from the global financial

01:19:56.440 --> 01:20:08.120
[Guest]: crisis. The US under its newly anointed President, Barack Obama, moved extraordinarily swiftly to

01:20:08.120 --> 01:20:17.160
[Guest]: restore health to the banking system. Huge sums of money were invented, conjured up, pumped in all

01:20:17.160 --> 01:20:24.200
[Guest]: kinds of programs with different names, etc, etc, including the very, very vast tarpaulin of the

01:20:24.200 --> 01:20:31.160
[Guest]: TARP were made available to banks, banks were shut down, banks were bought by other banks,

01:20:31.720 --> 01:20:41.480
[Guest]: all under the very, very watchful eye of Treasury and the Federal Reserve and the President. And

01:20:42.040 --> 01:20:48.360
[Guest]: this despite the fact that if you are to take a call between Wall Street and Main Street,

01:20:48.360 --> 01:20:53.480
[Guest]: you would say that Barack Obama represented Main Street rather than Wall Street. But the first

01:20:53.480 --> 01:21:01.640
[Guest]: thing that he did was to repair Wall Street. And in a sense, if you look back at the political

01:21:01.640 --> 01:21:08.360
[Guest]: economy of the US, the fact that Main Street sort of got neglected is a major reason I would say for

01:21:09.080 --> 01:21:18.360
[Guest]: the Trump ascendancy. But the reason I bring the US up is that somehow in India, we have this

01:21:18.360 --> 01:21:28.040
[Guest]: enormous culture of forbearance, sweeping things under the table, ignoring the problems and hoping

01:21:28.040 --> 01:21:39.000
[Guest]: that they will go away, etc, etc, etc. So, the kind of rapidity and aggression with which the

01:21:39.000 --> 01:21:48.680
[Guest]: US financial system was repaired, didn't find expression over here. And we sort of pretended

01:21:48.680 --> 01:21:53.480
[Guest]: that everything could continue pretty much as it was, that this was a blip, and it would get

01:21:53.480 --> 01:22:00.360
[Guest]: restored. And, you know, of course, a lot of good things happened, because as a financial system,

01:22:00.360 --> 01:22:06.440
[Guest]: the rest of the world got restored, and interest rates got lowered to new lows, in fact, to

01:22:06.440 --> 01:22:12.600
[Guest]: negative numbers, money started flowing in again, and we all sort of figured that it's all right.

01:22:12.600 --> 01:22:19.880
[Guest]: But as we're seeing over the last two or three years, our banking system was actually getting

01:22:19.880 --> 01:22:27.960
[Guest]: unhealthier and unhealthier and unhealthier. Two things happened. One is that I think Raghuram

01:22:27.960 --> 01:22:35.080
[Guest]: Rajan realized that we needed to look at bank loans much more severely. And therefore, he mandated

01:22:35.080 --> 01:22:42.920
[Guest]: much, much stricter norms. So, in fact, he forced the uncovering of a lot of bad loans and put much,

01:22:42.920 --> 01:22:47.080
[Guest]: much more stringent discovery norms in place and so on, to the extent that you see,

01:22:47.720 --> 01:22:53.560
[Guest]: not as a mainstream of thought, but as almost a trial balloon going up right now, which is,

01:22:53.560 --> 01:22:59.000
[Guest]: perhaps we shouldn't have been so rigid. You know, I don't want to comment on that. I think

01:22:59.000 --> 01:23:04.200
[Guest]: it's always good to, to see what's happening and then perhaps take a view on it. But that view

01:23:04.200 --> 01:23:12.200
[Guest]: should be in public, not hidden in subcommittees and not even coming to boards and not being talked

01:23:12.200 --> 01:23:20.920
[Guest]: about and so on. So, the banking system was getting increasingly rotten. And what we saw,

01:23:21.480 --> 01:23:28.840
[Guest]: if we go back to my starting point about investment, we saw massive investment taking place.

01:23:28.840 --> 01:23:35.880
[Guest]: And a lot of it turned out to be malinvestment. So, you saw

01:23:38.360 --> 01:23:41.880
[Guest]: organized, you saw Atata, for example, you know,

01:23:43.720 --> 01:23:48.360
[Guest]: investing in steel in the US and in Jaguar Land Rover.

01:23:48.360 --> 01:23:59.480
[Guest]: Jaguar Land Rover. You saw a company which is doing spectacularly well and were the pioneers

01:23:59.480 --> 01:24:04.760
[Guest]: and the brand leaders in television entertainment, which is or not the company, the group,

01:24:04.760 --> 01:24:18.120
[Guest]: the Z group, investing in infrastructure and resources and dish TV and so on so forth.

01:24:19.320 --> 01:24:27.480
[Guest]: So, it was almost as if this enormous amount of money that was on tap made people think,

01:24:27.480 --> 01:24:33.320
[Guest]: oh, there's so much money, what can I do with it? During a period where again, we were back to

01:24:33.320 --> 01:24:39.320
[Guest]: new lows in interest rates in India, India had always been a very, very high interest rate regime.

01:24:39.320 --> 01:24:44.040
[Guest]: But now there was all of this money. And there were all of these people who were relatively

01:24:44.600 --> 01:24:50.200
[Guest]: new businessmen who had done extraordinarily well in fields, which was now saying, you know,

01:24:50.200 --> 01:24:54.920
[Guest]: I'm a good businessman, business is business. And what can I do with all of this money?

01:24:54.920 --> 01:25:03.400
[Guest]: And then of course, we had just as with the US, we had this obsession with real estate.

01:25:04.200 --> 01:25:09.640
[Guest]: It was almost as though the word real was some sort of guarantee of real return.

01:25:10.920 --> 01:25:16.200
[Guest]: Real estate is real. So how can you lose in it? There are a million Indians being born every

01:25:16.200 --> 01:25:22.200
[Guest]: month, they need places to go to. India is urbanizing, therefore we need real estate.

01:25:22.200 --> 01:25:34.680
[Guest]: And this sort of story started feeding on itself. And we had a bull run in real estate, which was

01:25:34.680 --> 01:25:43.800
[Guest]: co-terminus with that in the US. So 2007, 2008, we saw a blip in that. But then as the money started

01:25:43.800 --> 01:25:53.160
[Guest]: coming back in, the graphs resumed, they didn't go down. And so people kept building. And

01:25:55.000 --> 01:26:03.800
[Guest]: regulation, very, very, very, very poor people were using advances from buyers, not to build

01:26:05.320 --> 01:26:11.240
[Guest]: against what the advances were for, but to buy more land. And we had this lovely word being

01:26:11.240 --> 01:26:17.800
[Guest]: tossed around land banks. You know, almost as though the fact that you had land meant that the

01:26:17.800 --> 01:26:24.280
[Guest]: money was safe. Whereas you were bidding up the price, and there were often no buyers for it.

01:26:24.280 --> 01:26:29.080
[Guest]: So we saw this enormous, enormous amount of investment taking place.

01:26:30.840 --> 01:26:37.000
[Guest]: And investment rates in India just kept going up. And savings rates kept going up. The savings

01:26:37.000 --> 01:26:44.600
[Guest]: rates in India peaked in 2008, at like 38, 39%, which was, again, unprecedented. And that coupled

01:26:44.600 --> 01:26:51.400
[Guest]: with the money that was coming in from abroad, meant that your investment rates and fixed capital

01:26:51.400 --> 01:27:01.560
[Amit Varma]: were like 40%. And what also happened during this period is that banks made a lot of malinvestments,

01:27:01.560 --> 01:27:06.360
[Amit Varma]: and they continue to double down on it rather than declare something as a bad loan, for example,

01:27:06.360 --> 01:27:07.320
[Amit Varma]: which is not coming back.

01:27:07.320 --> 01:27:13.080
[Guest]: As I said, there was this, we don't want to recognise, we don't want to recognise bad loans,

01:27:13.080 --> 01:27:13.400
[Guest]: you know.

01:27:14.440 --> 01:27:18.440
[Amit Varma]: And also the short term investments of the bankers and the officials in charge come into play,

01:27:18.440 --> 01:27:23.160
[Amit Varma]: because their incentives are that, you know, during their term, they don't want to look

01:27:23.160 --> 01:27:28.200
[Amit Varma]: bad by declaring bad loans and all of that, because in some sense, it seems to reflect on them,

01:27:28.200 --> 01:27:32.680
[Amit Varma]: they would rather give more loans, throw good money after bad, and kick the problem down the

01:27:32.680 --> 01:27:33.800
[Guest]: road for the next guy to solve.

01:27:33.800 --> 01:27:38.040
[Guest]: Yeah, so to stay with the issue of incentives, you know, again, we have the principal agency

01:27:38.040 --> 01:27:43.480
[Guest]: problem. And it's very clear if you draw a sharp line, obviously, there are people on both sides

01:27:43.480 --> 01:27:48.440
[Guest]: of the line. But if you draw a sharp line between the private banks and the public sector banks,

01:27:48.440 --> 01:27:53.800
[Guest]: it's very clear that there's a, there's a radical difference in terms of non performing assets,

01:27:53.800 --> 01:27:55.800
[Amit Varma]: which is a polite word for bad loans.

01:27:55.800 --> 01:27:58.040
[Guest]: In fact, I've had an episode on that as well.

01:27:58.600 --> 01:28:03.080
[Guest]: It's very clear that, you know, you can really draw a sharp line in between. There are exceptions

01:28:03.080 --> 01:28:10.520
[Guest]: on both sides. But as an aggregate, the difference in NPA ratios, factor of three is to one or

01:28:10.520 --> 01:28:16.360
[Guest]: something like that. So it's very clear that there's that agency problem as well.

01:28:17.080 --> 01:28:23.960
[Guest]: And again, this is not, you know, people always want to hedge that and mealy mouth it and so on.

01:28:23.960 --> 01:28:28.680
[Guest]: And so 10 days ago, when we had the 50th anniversary of bank nationalization,

01:28:28.680 --> 01:28:32.680
[Guest]: I saw all these articles which said bank nationalization was necessary, and it was

01:28:33.240 --> 01:28:36.280
[Guest]: imperative and so on. I couldn't even bring myself to read them.

01:28:36.280 --> 01:28:38.040
[Guest]: Horrendous and economically illiterate.

01:28:38.040 --> 01:28:43.480
[Guest]: Yeah, completely, completely. So, especially when we've seen the results, it's not that the

01:28:43.480 --> 01:28:50.440
[Guest]: jury is out, the jury is in. The results are very clear. Anyway, so I think there was a third

01:28:50.440 --> 01:29:01.320
[Guest]: factor. This is only my own personal idiosyncratic spin on it, which is that loans are priced in

01:29:01.320 --> 01:29:10.280
[Guest]: nominal terms, which means that as far as a loan is concerned, aside from interest, today's money

01:29:10.280 --> 01:29:17.080
[Guest]: is as good as yesterday's money. There's no accounting for the change in the real buying

01:29:17.080 --> 01:29:25.560
[Guest]: power of that money. Now, what happens as a result is that if your loan book is going up by

01:29:26.840 --> 01:29:36.920
[Guest]: 20 percent per annum in a situation where GDP is going up by eight or nine percent and inflation

01:29:36.920 --> 01:29:47.640
[Guest]: is going up by seven or eight percent, then even if you have a static market share of the GDP,

01:29:48.360 --> 01:29:53.160
[Guest]: your loan book is going to go up by 16 percent per annum. That's the nominal growth in GDP.

01:29:54.040 --> 01:30:00.360
[Guest]: Now, what this does is that if a loan from five years ago goes bad, in those five years,

01:30:00.360 --> 01:30:09.240
[Guest]: your loan book has doubled and therefore the share of the NPA to your assets today is,

01:30:10.280 --> 01:30:17.240
[Guest]: has halved. Right? Now, this was the rate at which the economy was growing in nominal terms,

01:30:17.240 --> 01:30:28.520
[Guest]: 2008, 9, 10, etc., etc., etc. Since then, what has happened is that the GDP in real terms,

01:30:28.520 --> 01:30:33.000
[Guest]: nobody knows the number, let's say it's six percent, inflation is, let's say, three percent.

01:30:33.000 --> 01:30:41.320
[Guest]: So, now your GDP is growing at nine percent per annum. For the real value of that bad loan made

01:30:41.320 --> 01:30:50.280
[Guest]: some years ago to half is now not going to take five years, but ten years. And therefore, the

01:30:51.320 --> 01:30:56.840
[Guest]: weight of old bad loans in your system starts showing up much earlier.

01:30:56.840 --> 01:31:00.120
[Guest]: So, a combination of a slowing economy,

01:31:01.800 --> 01:31:10.440
[Guest]: slowing inflation, and all of those horrible loans made when real estate was fashionable,

01:31:11.240 --> 01:31:15.880
[Guest]: and very important in our country, which is a more microeconomic thing,

01:31:16.680 --> 01:31:23.880
[Guest]: there was this enormous drive towards PPP, public-private partnership in infrastructure.

01:31:23.880 --> 01:31:29.080
[Guest]: Everybody jumped into it. Everybody thought it was a great idea. And I have to say, so did I.

01:31:29.080 --> 01:31:35.720
[Guest]: So, I'm not saying, you know, told you so. Everybody jumped into PPP. But as it turns out,

01:31:35.720 --> 01:31:40.360
[Guest]: the models were not thought through carefully. There was no clarity on how the repayment would

01:31:40.360 --> 01:31:47.400
[Guest]: come. And so, people with absolutely no experience of how to recover money from infrastructure

01:31:47.400 --> 01:31:56.360
[Guest]: projects in an economy and a regulation system, which is still fairly socialist and it's sort of,

01:31:56.360 --> 01:32:04.200
[Guest]: oh, how can you charge people so much? Oh, let's stop toll on this. Oh, we can't charge flyers so

01:32:04.200 --> 01:32:11.320
[Guest]: much to take off from Delhi Airport, etc., etc., etc. So, here were all these people who didn't

01:32:11.320 --> 01:32:19.000
[Guest]: know how to roll out infrastructure projects, whose background was in making television shows or

01:32:19.640 --> 01:32:27.480
[Guest]: running trucking systems or you name it, all jumping into PPP because it was fashionable

01:32:27.480 --> 01:32:33.880
[Guest]: and because they were going to get brownie points from their local politician for setting up 20

01:32:33.880 --> 01:32:38.680
[Guest]: miles of toll road or whatever, all jumping into this game without any clue as to how to manage

01:32:38.680 --> 01:32:45.400
[Guest]: them. And more importantly, without a clear political shift having been made in favor of

01:32:45.400 --> 01:32:53.960
[Guest]: people paying for infrastructure. So, all of these went horribly belly up. And so, when you have this

01:32:53.960 --> 01:33:01.720
[Guest]: kind of situation where something that becomes flavor of the decade and huge amounts of investment

01:33:01.720 --> 01:33:09.000
[Guest]: pile into it, which in our case was both housing as well as infrastructure as compared to the US

01:33:09.000 --> 01:33:14.760
[Guest]: where it was virtually a monoline story. And then they all turn bad. And now you have the same

01:33:14.760 --> 01:33:22.520
[Guest]: dynamic playing, which is banks having to write off money, investment committees and banks turning

01:33:22.520 --> 01:33:30.360
[Guest]: conservative, available funds going down, government getting strapped because the government is now the

01:33:30.360 --> 01:33:36.120
[Guest]: sole owner and therefore you can't mobilize funds from outside in order to recapitalize those banks,

01:33:37.080 --> 01:33:41.320
[Guest]: recapitalization funds being restricted, you have the entire credit system choking up.

01:33:42.600 --> 01:33:49.720
[Guest]: And so, credit growth starts going down. And that's what we've been seeing for the last

01:33:50.520 --> 01:33:55.640
[Guest]: few years. It should have happened 10 years ago, you know, and it's not one party versus the next

01:33:55.640 --> 01:34:04.600
[Guest]: because during these 10 years, we've had UPA 2 and we've had NDA 1, you know. So, I'm not pointing

01:34:04.600 --> 01:34:07.320
[Guest]: the blame at anyone political dispensation.

01:34:07.320 --> 01:34:12.520
[Amit Varma]: And the impulses of the state or the impulses of the state at the end of the day, which party is

01:34:12.520 --> 01:34:14.520
[Amit Varma]: in power is an unnis bis kafar akreli.

01:34:14.520 --> 01:34:24.760
[Guest]: Yeah, that's pretty clear now. And so, you had this massive credit crunch. And then for a whole

01:34:24.760 --> 01:34:33.000
[Guest]: host of reasons, some endogenous, some exogenous, you've also had slowing growth. Now, I think what

01:34:33.000 --> 01:34:40.520
[Guest]: we're seeing is exceedingly complex. It doesn't fall into the simple narrative with which one

01:34:40.520 --> 01:34:49.880
[Guest]: could perhaps express what happened in 2008. We're seeing slowing growth, we are seeing

01:34:49.880 --> 01:34:59.320
[Guest]: obfuscation of reality, which means the data is not coming out accurately, which stands hugely in

01:34:59.320 --> 01:35:05.080
[Guest]: the way of finding solutions. Because if you don't know what the problem is, you can't find the

01:35:05.080 --> 01:35:10.440
[Guest]: solution. Almost pure riot, I have to say that, but one has to because that is the situation.

01:35:10.440 --> 01:35:15.960
[Amit Varma]: And I had an episode on the GDP with the economist Rajeshwari Sengupta a few weeks ago. So, I'd

01:35:15.960 --> 01:35:21.880
[Amit Varma]: recommend check that out. I learnt a lot in that episode.

01:35:21.880 --> 01:35:27.560
[Guest]: Yeah. And so, you know, we have a situation where for the last four years, we've been

01:35:27.560 --> 01:35:35.640
[Guest]: squabbling, or three years, we've been squabbling about what the GDP growth rate is. And even by

01:35:35.640 --> 01:35:42.040
[Guest]: the government's own numbers, it's 5.8% for the last quarter, and there's a government which said

01:35:42.040 --> 01:35:47.480
[Guest]: there would bring GDP up to 10%. Now, that's a pie in the sky, because to go back to what I

01:35:47.480 --> 01:35:52.600
[Guest]: earlier said, unless you have high savings and you have high investment, you're not going to have

01:35:52.600 --> 01:36:00.360
[Guest]: high growth. And the numbers that we do know is that savings rates have gone down from 38% to

01:36:00.360 --> 01:36:07.720
[Guest]: 32% or 33%, and that capital formation has gone down from 40% to the low 30%. So, obviously,

01:36:07.720 --> 01:36:16.040
[Amit Varma]: growth is going to come down. And in fact, all of these other indicators are so bad that it seems

01:36:16.040 --> 01:36:20.920
[Amit Varma]: implausible that the GDP is what the government says it is, it just fails the smell test.

01:36:20.920 --> 01:36:27.640
[Guest]: Yeah, it completely fails the smell test. And so, I sort of say, you know, it's somewhere between

01:36:27.640 --> 01:36:35.080
[Guest]: four and five plus, and I hesitate to go much over 5%. And... And we don't even understand the

01:36:35.080 --> 01:36:39.400
[Amit Varma]: full impact of demonetization, because so much of it was in the informal sector, which is most of

01:36:39.400 --> 01:36:45.560
[Amit Varma]: our economy. Yeah, which is no longer getting recorded. And yeah, so, you know, as I said,

01:36:45.560 --> 01:36:50.600
[Guest]: there were a whole host of both exogenous and endogenous factors. One of the endogenous factors

01:36:50.600 --> 01:36:56.600
[Guest]: was certainly demonetization. And the ripple effects of that were very, very, very, very

01:36:56.600 --> 01:37:03.480
[Guest]: strong. And the ripple effects of that we don't know. One of the major exogenous factors, but

01:37:03.480 --> 01:37:09.960
[Guest]: you can't say it's entirely exogenous, because for a while we blamed slowing exports on the fact

01:37:09.960 --> 01:37:16.040
[Guest]: that global trade is shrinking. But at the same time, we know that Bangladesh is now exporting

01:37:16.040 --> 01:37:22.440
[Guest]: more governments than we are, where we used to be a global leader. We know that exports to GDP

01:37:22.440 --> 01:37:30.120
[Guest]: are going up in Vietnam. So as a small, relatively small global player, you can hugely increase your

01:37:31.000 --> 01:37:36.280
[Guest]: market share, but we're not able to do that. So that's a partly exogenous, partly endogenous

01:37:36.280 --> 01:37:44.040
[Guest]: factor. And as a capital short economy, one of the ways in which to grow is to increase your

01:37:45.000 --> 01:37:50.920
[Guest]: exports. And we've singularly failed at that, you know, most of the emerging nations have grown

01:37:50.920 --> 01:37:57.960
[Guest]: on the back of export led industry, we've completely failed to do that. So it's really now,

01:37:58.840 --> 01:38:03.480
[Guest]: for the last two or three years, we've been hearing what I actually find a fairly amusing

01:38:03.480 --> 01:38:11.080
[Guest]: story, which is that out of the drivers of economic growth, India is functioning on only

01:38:11.080 --> 01:38:17.160
[Guest]: one engine, which is consumption. I find that quite hilarious, because consumption is not an

01:38:17.160 --> 01:38:23.320
[Guest]: engine of economic growth. It's a product of economic growth. As I said, the engine of economic

01:38:23.320 --> 01:38:29.400
[Guest]: growth is investment. And where that comes from internal savings or external savings is,

01:38:30.360 --> 01:38:35.000
[Guest]: is a different matter. But you've got to have productive investments if you have growth,

01:38:35.000 --> 01:38:41.400
[Guest]: and you can't say that consumption is an engine. I mean, the Keynesian solution that everyone sort

01:38:41.400 --> 01:38:46.120
[Amit Varma]: of puts forward is that if the government just pumps more money into the economy,

01:38:46.120 --> 01:38:50.120
[Amit Varma]: consumption will go up because people will spend more. And if people spend more, and there is

01:38:50.120 --> 01:38:55.720
[Amit Varma]: greater demand for goods and services, that will be sparked and so on into a virtuous cycle.

01:38:57.240 --> 01:39:07.160
[Guest]: Well, you know, there is some truth to that. But it's a very, very distant truth. Because first,

01:39:07.160 --> 01:39:11.320
[Guest]: you've got to create that consumption. And then that consumption has got to go up enough for

01:39:11.320 --> 01:39:17.080
[Guest]: entrepreneurs to feel that now they need to expand capacity, and then they've got to expand

01:39:17.080 --> 01:39:22.520
[Guest]: the capacity. And then that expanded capacity is going to lead to more employment. So you know,

01:39:23.160 --> 01:39:29.480
[Guest]: it's a cycle that you have to continue for a long time before it starts kicking in. At this point

01:39:29.480 --> 01:39:37.480
[Guest]: in time in India, yes, that would probably be the only solution. But the fact is that

01:39:37.480 --> 01:39:43.960
[Guest]: the fact is that our government's finances also now enormously stretched.

01:39:43.960 --> 01:39:48.520
[Amit Varma]: And any money that the government puts into the economy like this also has an opportunity cost,

01:39:48.520 --> 01:39:51.240
[Amit Varma]: it's coming from somewhere and could have been put to some other use.

01:39:51.240 --> 01:39:57.480
[Guest]: Absolutely. So we, you know, the favorite phrase is crowding out. So government investment crowds

01:39:57.480 --> 01:40:05.400
[Guest]: out private investment. Not from the point of view of making it difficult for me to set up a

01:40:05.400 --> 01:40:09.720
[Guest]: factory because government has bought the land, but from a financial point of view, because

01:40:10.840 --> 01:40:18.040
[Guest]: there'll be less credit available for you, less credit available. And, you know, there is,

01:40:20.280 --> 01:40:27.160
[Guest]: at a recent colloquium on the political, well, on India post budget,

01:40:27.160 --> 01:40:34.120
[Guest]: Yamini Iyer of central of the Center for Policy Research made a very perceptive speech,

01:40:34.680 --> 01:40:41.000
[Guest]: only hindsight will tell us whether she's right or not. But her analysis of the narrative and the

01:40:41.000 --> 01:40:46.040
[Guest]: way it shifted over the last few years, I thought was very, very sharp, where she said, is that we

01:40:46.040 --> 01:40:55.080
[Guest]: moved away from the current leadership of the economy, describing it as a vibrant, growing

01:40:55.080 --> 01:41:08.920
[Guest]: economy, to talking about transfers and talking about redistribution as being the main narrative.

01:41:08.920 --> 01:41:14.520
[Guest]: I thought that was really, really perceptive, because that dialogue is completely gone about

01:41:14.520 --> 01:41:19.720
[Guest]: India being the fastest growing large economy in the world, and we're going to grow at 10% per

01:41:19.720 --> 01:41:27.800
[Amit Varma]: 10% per annum, etc, etc. And, and it reeks of desperation. What you're implicitly admitting

01:41:27.800 --> 01:41:33.880
[Amit Varma]: with that is that the pool is not growing, the pie is not growing large, quickly enough for

01:41:33.880 --> 01:41:38.520
[Guest]: everyone to benefit from it. So what little there is of it, we are going to distribute,

01:41:38.520 --> 01:41:43.320
[Amit Varma]: and we are going to do it in populist ways and try to win votes for it and spin it with all these

01:41:43.320 --> 01:41:49.800
[Amit Varma]: different narratives. But actually, we are just screwing everybody. Absolutely, absolutely. And,

01:41:49.800 --> 01:41:56.440
[Guest]: you know, we seem to have, we seem to have this ability in terms of governance and so on, so forth,

01:41:57.000 --> 01:42:06.200
[Guest]: to get to get some things desperately wrong. So, for example, there was this huge dialogue about

01:42:06.200 --> 01:42:15.000
[Guest]: make in India, etc, etc, etc. The fact is that in the last two months, I've got two sets of notices

01:42:15.000 --> 01:42:22.840
[Guest]: from the income tax relating to angel tax. You know, you can't get something as straight as that,

01:42:22.840 --> 01:42:32.120
[Guest]: which is that a tax that was created to try and prevent the army transfer of funds into shell

01:42:32.120 --> 01:42:37.080
[Guest]: companies, that income tax officer can't make out the difference between a startup and a shell

01:42:37.080 --> 01:42:42.760
[Guest]: company in some by lane in Calcutta. You know, there's something seriously wrong in the

01:42:42.760 --> 01:42:48.360
[Guest]: communication between the economic high command and the income tax department. If you can't make

01:42:48.360 --> 01:42:53.560
[Guest]: that out, you know, 21 year old can make out the difference between a shell company and a startup.

01:42:53.560 --> 01:43:02.840
[Guest]: You know, we still haven't been able to sort out ports and infrastructure relating to exports.

01:43:03.400 --> 01:43:13.000
[Guest]: So, all this stuff is just empty rhetoric. And you can game the making in the ease of doing business

01:43:14.120 --> 01:43:20.840
[Guest]: statistics by concentrating on what happens in Bombay and Delhi, just as you can game any exam.

01:43:20.840 --> 01:43:25.800
[Amit Varma]: But I mean, any metric can be gamed and any data which is brought out by the government can be

01:43:25.800 --> 01:43:31.400
[Guest]: manipulated. So what does it all mean? Yeah, but if you ask if you ask any businessman off the

01:43:31.400 --> 01:43:38.760
[Guest]: record, the compliance demands have gone up. And India has now become the biggest exporter of

01:43:39.400 --> 01:43:47.880
[Guest]: millionaires after China. That's really serious summit. And the way in which it's happening is

01:43:47.880 --> 01:43:56.040
[Guest]: a lot of small and medium sized businessmen have decided it's not really worth it, running

01:43:56.040 --> 01:44:03.640
[Amit Varma]: businesses. And I've spoken to businessmen, friends of mine who are disgusted, who are thinking of

01:44:03.640 --> 01:44:08.440
[Amit Varma]: leaving who keep talking about, you know, if we could just shut down our factories, blah, blah,

01:44:08.440 --> 01:44:13.480
[Amit Varma]: and leave tomorrow, we could and some of them in fact, say that GST, the way it's being implemented

01:44:13.480 --> 01:44:19.960
[Amit Varma]: and carried out is far worse for them than demonetization. Sure, sure, the compliance costs

01:44:19.960 --> 01:44:27.000
[Guest]: are enormous. And the government instead of making it easier to pay taxes and so on making it more

01:44:27.000 --> 01:44:35.800
[Guest]: and more difficult. And, you know, all of these operate at the margin. But the fact is that

01:44:35.800 --> 01:44:44.280
[Guest]: if you a lose millionaires, be if you move money from rich people to poor people,

01:44:45.480 --> 01:44:51.400
[Guest]: both of them result in lower savings rates. Because the marginal propensity to consume

01:44:51.400 --> 01:44:59.320
[Guest]: of the poor is much higher than that of the rich, you know, and if and the other shift that's

01:44:59.320 --> 01:45:04.120
[Guest]: happened, especially over the last month or two, is that overseas investors are looking at India

01:45:04.120 --> 01:45:13.800
[Guest]: askance. And so each of these in numerical terms may not be a huge amount, but you know, you add a

01:45:13.800 --> 01:45:19.080
[Guest]: few basis points here and a few basis points there and take that away from savings and hence

01:45:19.080 --> 01:45:26.840
[Guest]: investments and so on, you end up with fairly significant drops in the number of people who

01:45:26.840 --> 01:45:32.200
[Guest]: invest in India. You end up with fairly significant drops in economic growth at a time when the

01:45:32.200 --> 01:45:40.120
[Guest]: government is really, really hungry for political reasons to put money into current expenditure

01:45:40.120 --> 01:45:48.200
[Guest]: rather than into investments. And so you basically undermine the long term, the long term

01:45:48.760 --> 01:45:54.680
[Guest]: productive capacity of the government. And to go back to, you know, my what we were talking about,

01:45:54.680 --> 01:46:03.160
[Guest]: which is about investments and so on. All of this is happening against a backdrop where

01:46:06.360 --> 01:46:10.360
[Guest]: for the last four or five years, there was this sort of

01:46:11.400 --> 01:46:17.080
[Guest]: rah-rah around the Indian economy, you know, fastest growing economy, major economy in the

01:46:17.080 --> 01:46:25.080
[Guest]: world, a dynamic focused government, which doesn't have to mess with what's happening in parliament,

01:46:25.080 --> 01:46:31.720
[Guest]: and therefore pro growth, etc, etc, etc. And your introduction about narrative, you know,

01:46:31.720 --> 01:46:37.400
[Guest]: this was a very powerful narrative and it carried, it carried the stock markets through.

01:46:37.400 --> 01:46:47.080
[Guest]: Now, the same company with the same profitability today, if it's looking at high growth for the next

01:46:47.080 --> 01:46:53.480
[Guest]: five years, is going to command a very, very different price from the same company with the

01:46:53.480 --> 01:47:02.440
[Guest]: same profit number today where growth is looking shaky. And I think that Indian stock markets have

01:47:02.440 --> 01:47:08.520
[Guest]: not yet reckoned with the disjunct between the way in which stock markets are getting priced

01:47:09.640 --> 01:47:19.720
[Guest]: and the underlying growth of the economy. You know, the price of Indian stocks is

01:47:21.240 --> 01:47:27.480
[Guest]: at least three standard deviations above the mean and that can't sustain for very long.

01:47:27.480 --> 01:47:33.960
[Guest]: And that's what brings me to what I see as just from that limited point of view, forget the

01:47:34.520 --> 01:47:42.840
[Guest]: economic or the financial or the fiscal or the jobs or the, or the other, the demographic crises

01:47:42.840 --> 01:47:51.640
[Guest]: in the country and so on, is to this, to this particular opportunity, you could say, for people

01:47:51.640 --> 01:47:58.440
[Guest]: like me to say, you know what, the stock market is grossly overpriced. A, protect yourself by

01:47:58.440 --> 01:48:05.400
[Guest]: taking some money off the table. And in that sense, you know, the last four or five years have

01:48:05.400 --> 01:48:16.120
[Guest]: been a slow motion, less intense sort of replay of what happened in, to me in 2007, where I said

01:48:16.120 --> 01:48:24.600
[Guest]: markets are going to crash. And they didn't, till they did, to everyone's thing, oh, you know,

01:48:24.600 --> 01:48:30.920
[Guest]: we're going to see a resurgence of investment and the power sector is going to mushroom because we

01:48:30.920 --> 01:48:38.840
[Guest]: have this new scheme of called Udaya or whatever it was, and infrastructure is going to boom,

01:48:38.840 --> 01:48:47.080
[Guest]: infrastructure is going to boom, etc, etc. And I say, you know what, it's not so easy. And people

01:48:47.080 --> 01:48:54.680
[Guest]: were selling it as a Modi story. And I was saying, you know, it's not, it's not Modi. It's about the

01:48:54.680 --> 01:49:02.600
[Guest]: fact that certain very, very, very hard headed, deep responses to the banking crisis need to be

01:49:02.600 --> 01:49:12.040
[Guest]: made, and they're not being made. And if you think Modi is going to do it, that's great. I was mildly

01:49:12.040 --> 01:49:19.640
[Guest]: hopeful that he would, but one didn't see that kind of break from incrementalism and hiding

01:49:19.640 --> 01:49:25.400
[Guest]: things under the carpet. In fact, in terms of hiding things under the carpet, the Modi government

01:49:25.400 --> 01:49:32.760
[Guest]: proved to be even more adroit than earlier governments. There are masters of narrative

01:49:32.760 --> 01:49:37.160
[Amit Varma]: management to the point that they seem to think perhaps correctly that narrative management is

01:49:37.160 --> 01:49:42.600
[Amit Varma]: all that matters. Governance does not. Optics is everything and the 2019 election seem to have

01:49:42.600 --> 01:49:48.440
[Amit Varma]: even vindicated that. But so my sort of follow up question is that, you know, at the start of the

01:49:48.440 --> 01:49:52.600
[Amit Varma]: show, I mentioned the different kinds of crisis that we're having, which have been decades in

01:49:52.600 --> 01:49:57.240
[Amit Varma]: building up, there's a jobs crisis, which is exacerbated by demographics in the sense that

01:49:57.240 --> 01:50:01.640
[Amit Varma]: demographic dividend is turning into a demographic disaster, you have 12 million people coming into

01:50:01.640 --> 01:50:05.560
[Amit Varma]: the workforce every month, 12 to 20 million, depending on where you take the numbers from

01:50:05.560 --> 01:50:14.360
[Amit Varma]: and every year, luckily, more than a million a month and 12 to 20 million every year. And

01:50:15.640 --> 01:50:20.920
[Amit Varma]: those jobs simply aren't there, which you would imagine would lead to youth unrest and not really

01:50:20.920 --> 01:50:26.040
[Amit Varma]: manifested in a big way yet. There is an agricultural crisis, which has been building up

01:50:26.040 --> 01:50:31.320
[Amit Varma]: for decades. And again, I've had episodes on that. And it's not necessarily the fault of any one

01:50:31.320 --> 01:50:37.000
[Amit Varma]: party or the other. But the fact of the matter is that this party also is doing nothing to solve it.

01:50:37.000 --> 01:50:43.560
[Amit Varma]: Plus, there is now this credit crisis and a different sort of financial crisis in the making

01:50:43.560 --> 01:50:49.560
[Amit Varma]: and a fiscal crisis and a fiscal crisis. So my two sort of questions for you is that number one,

01:50:49.560 --> 01:50:55.320
[Amit Varma]: you'd imagine that Luke something's got to give at some point, what could it possibly be? And the

01:50:55.320 --> 01:51:01.800
[Amit Varma]: second question is that what can now be done to mitigate this? And what is realistic to happen?

01:51:02.440 --> 01:51:09.880
[Guest]: As far as the second is concerned, I don't see anything that can be done in the short term. And

01:51:09.880 --> 01:51:20.760
[Guest]: governments are notoriously bad at solving long term problems. And to take a hard line

01:51:21.560 --> 01:51:28.680
[Guest]: on matters as we've seen in the past, especially in India, requires a crisis, a crisis that

01:51:28.680 --> 01:51:35.240
[Guest]: actually sort of wraps you in the face. You know, financial crises, economic crises are a long time

01:51:35.240 --> 01:51:42.920
[Guest]: in coming. The ingredients are all there. But when do they blow up? It requires a sharp discontinuity

01:51:42.920 --> 01:51:51.080
[Guest]: somewhere. And you can't, you can't pinpoint either the time or the manner of it.

01:51:52.920 --> 01:51:56.440
[Amit Varma]: And what strikes me about this one and why it might be deeper is it's not just an economic

01:51:56.440 --> 01:51:58.520
[Amit Varma]: crisis per se, it's a social crisis as well.

01:51:58.520 --> 01:52:00.120
[Guest]: But let me just stay with the economic crisis.

01:52:00.120 --> 01:52:00.680
[Amit Varma]: Sure.

01:52:00.680 --> 01:52:06.680
[Guest]: Just for a second. Which is that, you know, all of this is against the backdrop of

01:52:08.600 --> 01:52:15.720
[Guest]: very high provision of liquidity around the world. And if that for any reason had stopped,

01:52:15.720 --> 01:52:23.800
[Guest]: then the crisis in India would have, would have been deep and sharp. That's not happened as yet.

01:52:23.800 --> 01:52:31.000
[Guest]: And that's papered over some of the cracks. It's allowed us to keep going. Because even

01:52:31.000 --> 01:52:36.280
[Guest]: through the last three years, until literally until July, we were still getting money from

01:52:36.280 --> 01:52:40.760
[Guest]: abroad. People were still putting money in. People were still buying the India as a growth

01:52:40.760 --> 01:52:51.480
[Guest]: story kind of narrative. So I think that as long as there is global liquidity, and

01:52:51.480 --> 01:53:00.120
[Guest]: as long as a significant percentage of those who are those global investors were tasked with putting

01:53:00.120 --> 01:53:07.000
[Guest]: money into emerging markets coming into India, I think that that crisis may not strike very sharply.

01:53:07.640 --> 01:53:12.920
[Guest]: So, you know, maybe again, going back to my personal practice, maybe those shorts won't

01:53:12.920 --> 01:53:20.280
[Guest]: yield the same kind of x returns as they did in 2008. But I still prefer to be largely out of

01:53:20.280 --> 01:53:25.400
[Guest]: the markets than in them, even if I don't take huge, deep, short exposures.

01:53:28.600 --> 01:53:38.120
[Guest]: I believe that the crunch, when it comes, will come from the external sector.

01:53:38.120 --> 01:53:46.280
[Guest]: It's, it will come when we find it difficult to borrow money from abroad. It will come when

01:53:47.560 --> 01:53:56.600
[Guest]: when the Indian government finds it difficult to meet its payments. Because we still have,

01:53:56.600 --> 01:54:03.560
[Guest]: you know, we keep talking about our, our foreign reserves. But again, I find it very funny that

01:54:03.560 --> 01:54:09.640
[Guest]: we have this number of foreign exchange. Nobody talks about what we owe abroad, which is always

01:54:09.640 --> 01:54:15.640
[Guest]: larger than what we our reserves are, you know. So the fact is that on a daily basis,

01:54:16.520 --> 01:54:21.960
[Guest]: even though our bond markets are not as liquid as they should be, and there are restrictions on

01:54:21.960 --> 01:54:27.000
[Guest]: foreign borrowing and so on. But the fact is that on a daily basis, foreign investors are buying

01:54:27.000 --> 01:54:37.400
[Guest]: bonds, you know. And if the underlying economic reality continues to slide, a point in time will

01:54:37.400 --> 01:54:42.280
[Guest]: come when the government can manufacture whatever narrative it wants to as far as the Indian

01:54:42.280 --> 01:54:48.520
[Guest]: consumer is concerned. But foreign investors march to their own tune, you know, they're going to take

01:54:48.520 --> 01:54:56.920
[Guest]: their own call. And, and, and, and, and, and, and, and, and, and, and, and, and, and, and, and, and,

01:54:56.920 --> 01:55:01.160
[Guest]: and if at some point in time they decide, you know, these are not risks worth taking,

01:55:01.960 --> 01:55:05.480
[Guest]: then conditions can snowball very, very rapidly.

01:55:05.480 --> 01:55:08.760
[Amit Varma]: AMIT BHANDARI And what social manifestation

01:55:08.760 --> 01:55:09.640
[Amit Varma]: do you see of this?

01:55:09.640 --> 01:55:13.160
[Guest]: AMJad India has got to be the most tolerant country

01:55:13.160 --> 01:55:22.280
[Guest]: in the world. You know, we tolerate every kind of injustice, every kind of bad governance.

01:55:22.280 --> 01:55:27.400
[Guest]: I mean, we were having this conversation, Amit, about a month ago when I was in Bombay

01:55:27.400 --> 01:55:31.320
[Guest]: and we were having dinner and we were talking about the state of infrastructure.

01:55:31.320 --> 01:55:41.800
[Guest]: I find it inconceivable that in the year 2019, you can have one of the financial centers,

01:55:41.800 --> 01:55:49.280
[Guest]: if not of the world, then certainly of Asia, running on as antiquated and dilapidated and

01:55:49.280 --> 01:55:55.560
[Guest]: uncomfortable and sweaty a suburban train system as exists in Bombay.

01:55:55.560 --> 01:56:02.800
[Guest]: It's anti-diluvian, it's inhuman, and you have 12 people a day dying as a result of

01:56:02.800 --> 01:56:06.720
[Guest]: the way in which that rail system interfaces with the population.

01:56:06.720 --> 01:56:07.720
[Amit Varma]: And it's normalized.

01:56:07.720 --> 01:56:10.200
[Amit Varma]: We take it for granted and we have to get to work every day.

01:56:10.200 --> 01:56:12.160
[Guest]: So that's the spirit of Bombay, quote unquote.

01:56:12.160 --> 01:56:14.520
[Guest]: But this can only happen in Bombay.

01:56:14.520 --> 01:56:16.000
[Guest]: Elsewhere, this would lead to riots.

01:56:16.000 --> 01:56:17.920
[Guest]: You know, this can only happen in India.

01:56:17.920 --> 01:56:20.200
[Guest]: So we've internalized all of this bullshit.

01:56:20.200 --> 01:56:25.600
[Guest]: We've internalized the fact that the government can mistreat us whichever way it wants.

01:56:25.600 --> 01:56:33.360
[Guest]: And it's part of our legacy, our spirit, our tolerance, our passivity, our Hinduism, whatever

01:56:33.360 --> 01:56:34.360
[Guest]: else it is.

01:56:34.360 --> 01:56:35.360
[Guest]: And, you know,

01:56:35.360 --> 01:56:39.200
[Amit Varma]: Maybe it's just part of our majburi.

01:56:39.200 --> 01:56:40.200
[Amit Varma]: What do we do?

01:56:40.200 --> 01:56:46.320
[Guest]: Well, you know, so, but the thing is that majburi is an Indian word.

01:56:46.320 --> 01:56:50.160
[Guest]: And we've seen this movie in Latin America.

01:56:50.160 --> 01:56:59.200
[Guest]: And this movie of bad governance, of urban decay, of lack of jobs has led to extreme

01:56:59.200 --> 01:57:03.000
[Guest]: violence.

01:57:03.000 --> 01:57:09.920
[Guest]: India surprisingly has very low crime rates, very low homicide rates.

01:57:09.920 --> 01:57:11.760
[Guest]: So it is cultural.

01:57:11.760 --> 01:57:17.600
[Guest]: And I think the other thing is, which is also cultural, is the fact that families are much

01:57:17.600 --> 01:57:23.880
[Guest]: more tolerant of people within the family who don't do so well.

01:57:23.880 --> 01:57:30.320
[Guest]: And they don't get frustrated at young men particularly, because we also have one of

01:57:30.320 --> 01:57:33.800
[Guest]: the lowest female labor participation rates in the world.

01:57:33.800 --> 01:57:36.480
[Guest]: So women are not necessarily expected to bring in money.

01:57:36.480 --> 01:57:40.520
[Guest]: But the fact that the young man hasn't been able to get a job, you know, and he just sits

01:57:40.520 --> 01:57:45.120
[Guest]: around and he hasn't got a job and he keeps applying to government jobs which aren't available

01:57:45.120 --> 01:57:50.840
[Guest]: and he's not getting off his ass and going to sell newspapers at the corner or whatever

01:57:50.840 --> 01:57:52.560
[Guest]: it is to make a living.

01:57:52.560 --> 01:57:55.920
[Guest]: So we seem to take all of it in our stride.

01:57:55.920 --> 01:58:01.120
[Guest]: And on balance, even though as an economist, I really, on balance, that's probably a good

01:58:01.120 --> 01:58:02.120
[Guest]: thing.

01:58:02.120 --> 01:58:09.920
[Guest]: I'd much rather live in a, in a poor and passive society than in a violent, bullet riddled

01:58:09.920 --> 01:58:16.200
[Amit Varma]: one like, like Brazil, which is equally poor, but at some point on one less or something

01:58:16.200 --> 01:58:22.480
[Guest]: will give us for true, much less poor, nevertheless, very intolerant of all of that.

01:58:22.480 --> 01:58:27.960
[Amit Varma]: So to kind of round up this episode, let me ask you a question with which I sort of end

01:58:27.960 --> 01:58:33.040
[Amit Varma]: many of my episodes on whatever the subject of the episode is that, you know, you've painted

01:58:33.040 --> 01:58:36.840
[Amit Varma]: a very bleak picture of this current crisis.

01:58:36.840 --> 01:58:42.800
[Amit Varma]: In fact, a basket of crises, as it were, that we are undergoing right now.

01:58:42.800 --> 01:58:46.520
[Amit Varma]: Looking forward to the next 10 years, what's the best case scenario?

01:58:46.520 --> 01:58:48.840
[Guest]: What's the worst case scenario?

01:58:48.840 --> 01:59:03.920
[Guest]: The worst case scenario is that we slide towards a Latin American kind of situation of deep

01:59:03.920 --> 01:59:19.960
[Guest]: unrest and widespread impoverishment and deepening social fissures between the rich and the poor.

01:59:19.960 --> 01:59:30.800
[Guest]: Poor countries which get into financial difficulty end up with these kind of patterns of distribution.

01:59:30.800 --> 01:59:38.840
[Guest]: So that's the worst case scenario.

01:59:38.840 --> 01:59:57.760
[Guest]: The best case scenario is that we have a government that realizes that we need to encourage entrepreneurship

01:59:57.760 --> 02:00:08.040
[Guest]: in deed and through removing a lot of the barriers in place, of which there's an unending

02:00:08.040 --> 02:00:14.480
[Guest]: list both in industry and services as well as in agriculture.

02:00:14.480 --> 02:00:23.160
[Guest]: And that as a result, the current despondency among economic actors, I mean, entrepreneurs

02:00:23.160 --> 02:00:31.040
[Guest]: and industrialists lifts and because, you know, this whole aspect of animal spirits

02:00:31.040 --> 02:00:37.680
[Guest]: which Keynes talked about is a real fact.

02:00:37.680 --> 02:00:41.900
[Guest]: It's the biggest unknown in the entire equation.

02:00:41.900 --> 02:00:47.680
[Guest]: And if you can bring that back into the system, then the fact is that Indians are extraordinarily

02:00:47.680 --> 02:00:56.360
[Guest]: entrepreneurial and even though it's a thin slice, the best educated Indians are extraordinarily

02:00:56.360 --> 02:01:10.560
[Guest]: well educated and are extremely good at setting up businesses and finding the gap as it were.

02:01:10.560 --> 02:01:17.680
[Guest]: And so that's the best case scenario that we're able to encourage entrepreneurship and

02:01:17.680 --> 02:01:19.800
[Guest]: economic growth.

02:01:19.800 --> 02:01:28.160
[Guest]: Is it likely to happen in as short a period as five to ten years is something that worries

02:01:28.160 --> 02:01:40.120
[Guest]: me because when the wave changes from exuberance to pessimism, it takes a long time to reverse

02:01:40.120 --> 02:01:47.920
[Guest]: and all of the impulses of the current government, which has five out of those ten years at the

02:01:47.920 --> 02:01:54.840
[Guest]: very least to run seem to be towards control rather than encouragement.

02:01:54.840 --> 02:02:00.960
[Amit Varma]: And it's kind of tragic because the best case scenario, as you pointed out, is, you know,

02:02:00.960 --> 02:02:07.120
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I sort of look at Indian history as a tussle between the state and society and

02:02:07.120 --> 02:02:13.520
[Amit Varma]: society is madly creative and entrepreneurial and full of these animal spirits, but the

02:02:13.520 --> 02:02:18.360
[Amit Varma]: state has restricted society from reaching its full potential in a manner of speaking,

02:02:18.360 --> 02:02:19.960
[Amit Varma]: which continues to the present day.

02:02:19.960 --> 02:02:24.000
[Amit Varma]: And the best case scenario in this case, to put your words slightly differently, is really

02:02:24.000 --> 02:02:27.280
[Amit Varma]: the state getting out of the way of society.

02:02:27.280 --> 02:02:30.560
[Amit Varma]: And kind of the opposite seems to be happening.

02:02:30.560 --> 02:02:31.560
[Guest]: Absolutely.

02:02:31.560 --> 02:02:38.760
[Guest]: Moving towards tighter and tighter and tighter, top down control rather than letting.

02:02:38.760 --> 02:02:49.000
[Guest]: So to put it in a third way, which is this gorgeous word, very simple word is trust.

02:02:49.000 --> 02:02:54.520
[Guest]: I think those societies do best where there's widespread trust in the system.

02:02:54.520 --> 02:02:58.680
[Guest]: We're seeing trust squeezed out of the system.

02:02:58.680 --> 02:03:05.360
[Guest]: We are seeing deeper and deeper polarizations and certainly going back to businessmen and

02:03:05.360 --> 02:03:08.720
[Guest]: businessmen are key to growth of an economy.

02:03:08.720 --> 02:03:13.640
[Guest]: Businessmen are more and more looking over their shoulders as to what they should do,

02:03:13.640 --> 02:03:21.040
[Guest]: where they should invest, whether their accounts are in order, etc., etc.

02:03:21.040 --> 02:03:28.160
[Guest]: And if you can't bring trust back into the system and amplify it, obviously, we're not

02:03:28.160 --> 02:03:32.400
[Guest]: going to get to Scandinavian levels of trust in five or 10 years.

02:03:32.400 --> 02:03:36.640
[Guest]: But let's at least start moving in that direction.

02:03:36.640 --> 02:03:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Then nothing's going to happen.

02:03:39.000 --> 02:03:42.640
[Amit Varma]: Maybe the best case scenario is that things will get so bad that we are forced to move

02:03:42.640 --> 02:03:43.640
[Amit Varma]: in that direction, Mohit.

